WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:22.000
Good morning. I'm Emily Crosby and we're here at the University of Southern Mississippi with Dean Eddie Holloway on December 2nd, 2015 as part of the Civil Rights History Project,

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:30.000
which is co-sponsored by the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:34.000
And with me are John Bishop and Guha Shankar.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:36.000
And well, good morning.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:37.000
Good morning.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:40.000
Thank you so much for doing the interview with us today.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:45.000
Could you start by telling us when and where you were born?

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:54.000
Eddie Holloway born 1952, September 26th, Hattiesburg, Mississippi.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:58.000
Can you tell me about your family and growing up?

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:04.000
Yes, my mother and father, Beatrice Holloway.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:14.000
Actually, she was a Gibson before she moved from York, Alabama and my father, Willie Holloway, was native to Hattiesburg, Mississippi.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:18.000
What kind of work did your parents do?

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:29.000
My mother was a beautician and I guess when her joy of fishing became as prominent, you could say she was a local fisherman.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:43.000
But my dad was a service provider and worked at the Meridian Fertilizer Company, which was a precursor to coastal chemicals.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:52.000
They made various ancestry fertilizers and I think the home office was Yazoo City, Mississippi.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:02:01.000
And his can't claim to fame and my bragging point is that he worked there for in excess of 60 years.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:05.000
Oh my. It's a long working home and one place.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:11.000
Yes, he told me when he went there, they paid her dollar a day and bet you couldn't make a dollar a day.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:14.000
So was it peace did they pay for peace work?

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:23.000
Well, he indicated that his task primarily was delivering fertilizer by the barrel from one location to the other.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:30.000
And the work was so extreme, again the pay was a dollar a day but they would bet you another dollar that you couldn't make a day.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:32.000
You could actually last the whole day?

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:36.000
Yes, so that was a two dollar a day work.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:54.000
And through the course of time he became the office custodian and even after the days of his retirement, the insurance of the company required that personnel be present at all time.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:03:02.000
So he stayed on the location as a watchman if you will.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:06.000
He was proud to his final illness.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:10.000
So he worked his almost entire life?

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:12.000
His entire life, yes.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:15.000
Did he like working for that company?

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:20.000
I think he loved maybe not the work but the people.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:35.000
I've until yet to find anybody that will make a statement ill of his being, his day-to-day walk.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:41.000
Many tell me that he would not sign a contract, he said that's my word.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:47.000
And I occasionally see people that still recall him for those attributes.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:50.000
So he was, maybe somebody people trusted?

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:54.000
Until now he's the best person that I ever remember meeting.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:55.000
Your father?

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:56.000
Yes.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:57.000
That's right.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:03:59.000
I wonder if we're feeling well, imagine.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:06.000
In where did your family live on Mobile Street?

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:07.000
904 Mobile Street.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:09.000
And where was your mom's shop?

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:13.000
My mom's shop was attached to the house.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:19.000
Bees Beauty Salon.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:22.000
Can you describe Mobile Street?

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:29.000
Mobile Street was a self-contained street as I remember it.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:37.000
Unless there were extreme needs, most of your needs were met inside of that Mobile Street area.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:39.000
There was a movie theater.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:51.000
There were probably 12 to 15 restaurants of some kind or the other, or taverns, or clubs or nightclubs or restaurants.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:05:06.000
As many beauty salons or barbershops, there was a physician's office, a dentist's office, a pharmacist.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:20.000
A couple of have-adassuries, tailor shops, at least six cleaners, four churches, a television repair shop, a watchmaker.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:26.000
At least four motels, if you will, a hotel, if you will.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:32.000
A couple of dance halls.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:39.000
And I would say the professionals of Hattiesburg, Mississippi lived in that area.

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:41.000
And was that really the heart of a black community?

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:44.000
That was the black community.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:46.000
Right there in that circle of people.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:48.000
Correct.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:56.000
Were the residences and the businesses were they sort of interspersed or was there a stretch that was just businesses within the United States?

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:03.000
Yeah, that was probably a four to five, maybe more stretch of businesses.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:20.000
And for the most part, the businesses were not co-mingled with residential living unless there would be a residential structure on the same lot behind or beside a business.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:28.000
What was it like for you as a young person to grow up in that atmosphere?

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:33.000
I remember happiness.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:49.000
It appeared from a towel's eye to live across the street from a school principal or to live next door to a teacher or to live across the street from executive types, if you will.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:07:01.000
The staffed the insurance office on what will be a street ought to go to church with the same people that lives in the catchment area of your house.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:13.000
There were always plenty of motivation intrinsic as well as external if you aspire to be.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:21.000
Did you frequent the businesses and would you be in that part of the community and go to the movie theater?

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:23.000
I would go to the drugstore.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:42.000
I would go to the cleaners from the time of my mother's birth every Saturday I would go to Williams cleaners to sit with Miss Thelma Williams because she cleaned my clothes from the point of my mom's death.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:53.000
Although I was not required to go up there, I felt an obligation to go to sit with her because she would be there dispensing clothes by herself.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:56.000
So you keep her company?

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:59.000
Was it busy?

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:11.000
The mobile street was so busy. There were points when you would have to exit the sidewalk to get into the street to traverse because it was a catchment area for 30 mile radius.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:28.000
All of the people in the McLain, Beaumont, Richton, areas, Wiggins, they would come to the mobile street area for beauty purposes, for clothing, for groceries.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:31.000
Every Saturday.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:37.000
Did Camp Shelby, was there business from Camp Shelby in the community?

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:39.000
Yes.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:55.000
I mean, the time that I'm speaking of, Camp Shelby was not an active army training facility as opposed to the service of Mississippi trained personnel.

00:08:55.000 --> 00:09:00.000
Okay. So was it just a training facility during World War II?

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:16.000
Yes. It was a training facility for World War I and II, but it primarily went for summer training camps and other trainings.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:26.000
It's always been an active training facility, but with less activity on the National Front.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:30.000
So was that like National Guard preparations?

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:47.000
Of course, at certain points National Guard personnel would come from various in the country or other states, but in terms of what I understood it to be at a point when there were 100,000 military personnel at Camp Shelby, but they would come into the city.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:51.000
That hasn't existed for quite a while.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:57.000
I know that I've heard that during World War II, which is really boosted in economy and income.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:01.000
What were you, where did you go to school, what were your schools like?

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:14.000
Well, initially I would have to see my kindergarten, the Maddie Robinson kindergarten, which was two and a half blocks from my house on New Orleans Street.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:25.000
And following that enrolled in W.H. Jones Elementary, Junior High School, which opened 1958 was my first grade year.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:42.000
I stayed there through nine years and then went to Royal High School, located on Royal Street, but later changed to Martin Luther King Avenue.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:48.000
So you mentioned that W.H. Jones Elementary and Junior High opened in 1958.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:53.000
So I'm assuming it's one of the schools that was built after the Brown decision.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:54.000
Correct.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.000
Were you aware of that at the time?

00:10:56.000 --> 00:11:02.000
Or were that, you know, what the impetus to sort of once the court ruled on integration,

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:05.000
and you specifically tried to make separate buddy cool more real?

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:10.000
Okay. No, I was not at that time in 1958.

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:29.000
But shortly after, somewhere prior to 64, 65, I remember hearing some of the educators discussing that.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:39.000
As I told you, my mom died. And Mrs. Sip, who was president of the Mississippi Teachers Association, lived across the street.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:52.000
There was an MTA (Mississippi Teachers Association) and an MTA (Mississippi Teachers Association). One catered to the African American teachers and the other two Caucasian teachers, but handing out of those houses.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:57.000
And I would say I was not the most athletic type.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:11:59.000
There would always be playing in the street.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:04.000
I would be in with one of them somewhere in an encyclopedia.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:14.000
And obviously, not welcome to listen to their conversations, but finding myself intrigued by some of the things that they were saying.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:28.000
And so as a result of those things, I did learn of the state's effort to stime me, full wholesale integration or desegregation by the building of schools such as W.H. Jones and Lillie Burney.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:33.000
And that was a wave that continued throughout the state of Mississippi.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:39.000
You mentioned the two separate organizations for teachers, for people that don't know.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:46.000
And I think the Mississippi Teachers Association was primarily African Americans.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:55.000
I remember being out of school and I remember that two days Monday Tuesday was set aside for black teachers.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:59.000
And Thursday Friday was set aside for white teachers.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:02.000
So when you say set aside, did they have a meeting?

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:04.000
A meeting place in Jackson.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:10.000
And so the white teachers would meet first.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:18.000
Well, I can't say which ones, but they did not meet together right.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:23.000
Well, you mentioned earlier that your mother passed away.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:25.000
How old were you when she passed away?

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:28.000
11.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:33.000
And at that point, you started spending more time with some of the teachers in the neighborhood.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:41.000
And I was always involved or connected by virtue of her being a beautician and most of them would come around.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:48.000
And as I told you, the majority of my teachers were members of my church.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:55.000
So even prior to her death, I would go to church with them because they live next door.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:59.000
Or I would go to teachers' meeting because they live next door.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:06.000
Or I would be there with one of their friends, excuse me, one of their children and we'll go along with them.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:11.000
So church was almost an extension of the school.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:19.000
Can you describe that a little bit for people sort of how the sort of interconnection between church and school?

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:25.000
Well, Mrs. Moore was my quiet director, if you will.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:29.000
Her sister-in-law, Mrs. Wilson, was my quiet director.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:39.000
Mrs. Moore, Mrs. Dice, was my third grade teacher and she was my Sunday School teacher.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:45.000
And I would go to church with her every time she went.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:50.000
Mrs. Knight, my fifth grade teacher, was my Sunday School teacher.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:55.000
And they were all superintendents of Sunday School or educational services.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:15:06.000
And our church, Mrs. Murdersrugh, who worked in conjunction with my second grade teacher, was a Sunday School teacher at Mount Carmel Baptist Church.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:17.000
Throughout the course of my earlier years in the environment, they were the same faces at different places.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:29.000
So in Sunday School or in church, they would know whether I was doing well in elementary school and vice versa.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:36.000
And we were anchored in the community living next door, three doors down across the street from.

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:51.000
So the educational voids that may have existed in my house were filled by virtue of my wanting to meet the expectations of those that were taking me with them everywhere.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:16:00.000
So I guess I'm sorry, I want to go in a couple directions. So it sounds like from a very young age you were hungry for education.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:03.000
Is that true assessment?

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:09.000
Yes, I don't know what I, hungry for education as opposed to I really wanted to be informed.

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:12.000
I really wanted to know.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:19.000
And I knew that there were things of importance that I did not know.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:24.000
And I would see the way that the teachers and the principals would dress.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:31.000
I would observe their cars and see their walk and their gate and the spunk of which they would get about.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:35.000
And I know I remember wanting some of that.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:43.000
So it appeared that the pathway to getting that was to impart be like them.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:47.000
Sounds like you were very much looked up to them.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:49.000
Correct.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:59.000
You said whatever educational void there might be in your home, how far did your parents were they able to go to school?

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:08.000
I don't know because my dad told me that he did not go to a Ureca school. He said he went to the Little Red Building.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:13.000
And from all I can gather, the Little Red Building was really a little yellow house.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:17.000
Now it may have been read at a point for him.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:22.000
And I tried desperately to find out about that Little Red House.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:30.000
With the history of Ureca High School, I do find that there was a Little Red House.

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:37.000
But I'm sure at that time, six grade or so, my mom, I don't know.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:51.000
But I knew, I remember one of the struggles that I had was every day when I'd get out of school, my dad would have a cardboard table on the porch waiting for me to get my lesson

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:54.000
before I could go out of the yard.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:56.000
And we really struggled.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:18:00.000
He referred to a zero as an alt.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:10.000
And that gripped me to knowing to the point of me absolutely saying despite his ability to count that he was archaic,

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:16.000
or that was old fashioned, or that wasn't current, or I don't need you teaching me.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:18.000
And every day challenged for me.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:30.000
So I think from that assumption, and from his writing, that I gathered that he was not formally educated.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:36.000
And certainly not like Miss Sip, Miss Cole, or the Wilson's.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.000
He didn't go.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:44.000
And then he was overalls to his work every day.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:47.000
That didn't remove my love for him.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:57.000
And it still today doesn't distract from me saying he was the best person that I know until this day.

00:18:57.000 --> 00:19:03.000
But I knew he was not formally schooled.

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:08.000
So you know, are there things that you learned from him, lessons that you want to learn from him?

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:20.000
Oh, goodness, my daughter today at 31.32 has asked me to write things down, and he's seen it.

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:24.000
I've had a life of challenge.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:27.000
And I don't say that with regret.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:33.000
I don't say that certainly for any pity or concern.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:37.000
But I cannot recall a life's challenge.

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:44.000
That in a moment of silence, a being sequestered from other person places of things,

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:49.000
that I can't recall something my day had told me that'll let me out of that.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:55.000
So I think he was extremely wise.

00:19:55.000 --> 00:20:02.000
I think I'll remember to say nothing to do with him, but I remember getting my first car.

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:12.000
And a guy came by riding on a bicycle with a big boom box, and he said, Eddie, I hear you got to your car.

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:15.000
I said, yeah, he said, what kind did you get?

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:17.000
I said, a Monte Carlo.

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:22.000
He said, man, that's a shiverly.

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:27.000
I said, yeah, he said, why you didn't get a GTO?

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:30.000
I said, I don't know anything about GTO.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:34.000
He said, so what's wrong with the shiverly?

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:38.000
He said, man, that's a poor man's car.

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:49.000
So I went on the porch and I said, daddy, is the shiverly made for poor man?

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:52.000
He said, well, first son, why are you asking me this?

00:20:52.000 --> 00:21:00.000
I said, well, a guy just told me that a shiverly was a poor man's car.

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:05.000
And a Pontiac was for a rich man.

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:09.000
He said, wasn't the guy that just stopped by here?

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:12.000
I said, yes.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:15.000
He said, I'm ashamed of you, baby.

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:17.000
I said, why?

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:27.000
He said, son, he's on a bicycle.

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:36.000
So he told in silence, very kind, never a gruff word.

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:40.000
I don't think I've ever heard him say damn or heal,

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:45.000
but I can recall his wisdom.

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:47.000
Does that make sense?

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:49.000
Yes.

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:54.000
You must have had a big impact on your family to raise your mother.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:55.000
Yes.

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:56.000
You said you were an only child.

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:59.000
Only child.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:04.000
Do you have any memories of those days about how you and your father co-cute that?

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:15.000
Well, it was an abrupt set of circumstances.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:22.000
My aunt came the same day from Alabama and her daughter and husband.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:28.000
And she remained with me until the last day of school.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:33.000
And they took me to Alabama.

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:39.000
That has to be the beginning of my civil rights history.

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:47.000
They were wise but totally uneducated, formally.

00:22:47.000 --> 00:23:02.000
But they lived and breathed civil rights, voting, watching the news every day.

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:12.000
Oh, did they love Martin Luther King and all of the civil rights workers.

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:20.000
And they were consumed with getting an education,

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:35.000
becoming educationally astute and to fight poverty.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:45.000
They instilled in me a heaping dose of pride, pride in person,

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:48.000
pride in appearance,

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:57.000
pride in the speech decor, never borrow, never request, never be,

00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:04.000
put your best foot forward every day.

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:08.000
And that was so overwhelming to me.

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:15.000
They would take me to the lower echelon areas of the city of Birmingham

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:26.000
and take me to the steel mills on payday and to see the people coming from the long companies

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:32.000
to be paid, try to the people getting their chicks.

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:38.000
They would show me the mothers with kids on their hips waiting for the men to be paid.

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:41.000
And I remember I was talking about it just yesterday.

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:51.000
They said, eat, and our life and our death don't embarrass us like that.

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:54.000
We'll be gone.

00:24:54.000 --> 00:25:01.000
We never had children, but you uphold our standards.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:05.000
You save every month.

00:25:05.000 --> 00:25:09.000
You go to church every Sunday.

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:14.000
You work every day.

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:17.000
You don't beg for nothing.

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:21.000
Earn your respect.

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:29.000
That has come with the penalty because all that I have traversed and been with didn't understand that.

00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:35.000
So it never has been that I've been so egotistical that I saw myself better than others.

00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:42.000
But I guess I have tried to live up to an ears and louises and eight punches.

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:46.000
Eat it that your mother's gone.

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:48.000
We won't be here long.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:53.000
You might have to depend on yourself.

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:56.000
So they lived in Birmingham and then?

00:25:56.000 --> 00:26:01.000
They lived in Bessemer, Alabama, which is 12 miles from Birmingham.

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:04.000
And this must have been 64.

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:07.000
64, 65.

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:18.000
Every holiday, every weekend, or every period of time when there was school without I'd take that train that next morning at 8 o'clock and go there.

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:24.000
Bicycle, baseball, and during the earlier years they would send my books

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:28.000
because the principal would cross the old diagonally across the street.

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:31.000
So he would know my classes that I needed.

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:36.000
And they would box those books and send them to me in Alabama.

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:39.000
And how long did you stay with your relatives in Alabama?

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:41.000
Every summer.

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:47.000
Yeah, all but at times when I would get a job of sort,

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:50.000
I disliked it.

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:52.000
They were so strict.

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:58.000
I mean sometimes two, three, four baths a day.

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:05.000
And even to the point of ironing your handkerchiefs and your underwear,

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:07.000
they were meticulous.

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:15.000
They ironed paper bags for Lewis to take his lunch to the steel meals.

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:19.000
So they said that if you would show a wrinkle bag,

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:23.000
it would indicate that that bag had been used before.

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:31.000
So yes, their concerns were to an extreme,

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:35.000
but I never lost focus of what their intentions were.

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:39.000
I know I grew weary of them.

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:42.000
As a young boy.

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:45.000
But I know that I would always need to go see them.

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:48.000
I know that I would always need to call them.

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:49.000
Puyland School here.

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:51.000
They would send me clothes.

00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:53.000
Some of which I would want to wear.

00:27:53.000 --> 00:27:56.000
Others I'd want to get rid of.

00:27:56.000 --> 00:27:59.000
Were you allowed to do that or did you have to wear them?

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:03.000
Oh, I could not because they may come down and want to see them.

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:05.000
So I just didn't wear them.

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:10.000
I didn't wear the red socks or the pink socks or the yellow socks.

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:23.000
But I knew on a given day I would get a letter or a package or a phone call of love.

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:29.000
I knew that I had everlasting friends and relatives.

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:32.000
And they would make sure I knew that.

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:36.000
That the others around me didn't care like they care.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:41.000
You just mentioned that your aunt and uncle would send you these packages.

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:42.000
Oh, yeah.

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:44.000
Bright colors and stuff.

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:45.000
Yeah, in something magazine.

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:53.000
I don't know what JC Penney or Sears, they would see combination of yellow shirt, yellow socks, red shirt, red socks.

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:57.000
Oh, and that's what they would send me in the mail.

00:28:57.000 --> 00:29:00.000
And I tried it.

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:04.000
But as I told you, I won't wear red socks anymore.

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:06.000
What happened when you wore?

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:11.000
Oh, they asked me did I step on a nail that my ankles were bleeding.

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:12.000
That was it.

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:14.000
That was it.

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:17.000
You find a friend to share those red socks with?

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:19.000
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:23.000
You said that they really introduced you to civil rights.

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:24.000
Yes.

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:28.000
It was very fiery about it.

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:37.000
In 1964, so if you're in Birmingham or Bessimer, right next to Birmingham in 1964, that would have been right after the big demonstration.

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:38.000
Correct.

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:40.000
Did they participate in that?

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:45.000
No, they did not march.

00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:50.000
They would be ones that would have given as much money as they could.

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:55.000
They would have gone to the church meetings.

00:29:55.000 --> 00:30:14.000
Would have participated by virtue of their social clubs that they would belong to those clubs who make donations to funds that would be used to bond people out of jail.

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:28.000
I can remember their interests consuming them inside of the walls of their home.

00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:33.000
But they weren't ones that would be rallying in the street.

00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:39.000
They would have been at that time 60 plus years of age.

00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:43.000
I was telling my family on the day goodness.

00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:48.000
They were 65 when they took a little key in at 11.

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:52.000
How gracious.

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:57.000
That sort of explains at least some of their expectations for you.

00:30:57.000 --> 00:31:07.000
Did you ever, I don't exactly know how much was going on in Birmingham at that particular time, but did they ever take you to mass meetings?

00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:11.000
No, they took me to the 16th Street Baptist Church.

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:16.000
They would take me to the Say Hey Burger restaurant.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:18.000
That was Willie Mays.

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:26.000
They would take me to the Birmingham Black Barons stadium where Willie Mays and others played.

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:32.000
They would show me the beauties if you will of Birmingham.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:40.000
When you say they took you to the 16th Street Baptist Church, were they talking to you about the bombing there?

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:41.000
Yes.

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:44.000
And other civil rights locations.

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:48.000
You remember what you thought about that as a young man?

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:54.000
You would have been almost the same age as the little girls.

00:31:54.000 --> 00:32:01.000
I don't think I understood what was really going on at the time.

00:32:01.000 --> 00:32:06.000
I knew that there were separate facilities.

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:22.000
I knew that I would have to work as hard, if not harder, to share in the beauty and the wealth of the country.

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:36.000
I know that I would have to, according to them, to be able to assimilate with attitude and with presentation.

00:32:36.000 --> 00:32:51.000
Because they, everyday, manners, table manners, greetings, poster.

00:32:51.000 --> 00:33:16.000
Those silent teachings that I may have not fully understood, but was trusting of them enough to accept going to church,

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:26.000
going down and asking the church to pray for me because my mother had died and to give me wisdom and knowledge.

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:28.000
Ask for wisdom and knowledge.

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:29.000
That was everyday.

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:39.000
Ask for wisdom and knowledge because once you leave us to go back to Haddie'sburg, you don't have that.

00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:43.000
They were speaking of relatives as such.

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:45.000
They were ethnocentric.

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:49.000
They wrote the word on that.

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:54.000
I'm not so sure that they did not try to take me from my dad.

00:33:54.000 --> 00:34:05.000
I think that was never a discussion of my consciousness, but I sensed by virtue of him always saying to me,

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:09.000
never let anybody talk to you against me.

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:12.000
Now, I'm not sure of all of that.

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:18.000
I was never really a father.

00:34:18.000 --> 00:34:22.000
But I was not able to affirm that.

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:24.000
They never told me that.

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:26.000
I asked them that.

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:29.000
What made you think you might not speak?

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:32.000
I had heard Scuttle but in the street.

00:34:32.000 --> 00:34:35.000
But never was able to confirm otherwise.

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:39.000
Berserotificates, all of that.

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:43.000
I mean, it's solid.

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:55.000
But I remember praying that if he lived to a hundred, never let that become an issue in his mind that I had heard that.

00:34:55.000 --> 00:34:59.000
Because he certainly didn't have any sense that he didn't treat you like.

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:01.000
He treated you like a person.

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:05.000
I've ever made in my life.

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:07.000
Okay.

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:12.000
So you talked about your relatives coming and supporting you after your mother passed away.

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:17.000
And earlier you talked to me about the community right around.

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:23.000
And that you had a lot of teachers right there who really kind of took you under their wing.

00:35:23.000 --> 00:35:27.000
Can you talk about that a little bit?

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:49.000
I think those teachers knew that the path to economic education and life freedoms all connected to education.

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:55.000
And for some odd reason I believed it.

00:35:55.000 --> 00:35:59.000
I believed because they told me that.

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:04.000
And I believed because my aunt and my cousins told me that.

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:10.000
And I believed it because my dad would always say,

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:15.000
get your lesson, get your lesson, get your lesson.

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:20.000
And additionally, that was what I call porch people.

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:31.000
So when I would walk from W.H. Jones as I walked past all of those houses, the people on the porch was saying,

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:33.000
you get your lesson a day.

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:35.000
You're going to be smart.

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:36.000
Be smart.

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:55.000
So I knew that there was some connection between getting your lesson, earning a living and having more than it would take just for a meager lifestyle.

00:36:55.000 --> 00:37:01.000
So it sounds like you're getting encouraged in that direction everywhere in your life?

00:37:01.000 --> 00:37:07.000
Those porch people, just sort of not go about it.

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:13.000
They were there and they always asked about school.

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:28.000
I don't know why, but I think they knew that the core effort to making life better started with school.

00:37:29.000 --> 00:37:38.000
And one even said, and I told you I didn't play a lot of ball didn't go here and there, but I would listen to what the law folk would say.

00:37:38.000 --> 00:37:47.000
One told me, son, there's a reason that people are killed when they try to go to get an education.

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:52.000
It must be something in education that will set you free.

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:54.000
I never knew what that meant.

00:37:54.000 --> 00:38:08.000
But when you looked at the integration of school or going to the separate facilities of saw all those other kinds of things, it really had an education connection.

00:38:08.000 --> 00:38:13.000
And so they were really talking directly about this resistance to school desegregation?

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:16.000
I think that's what they were talking about.

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:22.000
The people are that determined to keep you out?

00:38:22.000 --> 00:38:25.000
There was some high value to it.

00:38:25.000 --> 00:38:36.000
You mentioned earlier that you heard that when you first went to school, you didn't connect it to Brown or a young person.

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:39.000
But over time you heard the teachers talking about that.

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:42.000
You recall what they said?

00:38:42.000 --> 00:39:03.000
Oh, and I later affirmed it with the University of Southern Mississippi that it was known and strongly forecast that desegregation and integration would be a reality.

00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:23.000
But that in the state of Mississippi and other likewise states massive efforts to save that led to the funding of new schools so that it became a bargaining point, if you will, that would save it all for years to come.

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:43.000
So I've I've I've since that prior hearing N.R. Burger and all those other people talk about that and then learn to see that as a as a truth.

00:39:43.000 --> 00:39:53.000
Were they do recall did were they happy? I mean, I'm sure they were happy to have the new building, but did they?

00:39:53.000 --> 00:40:01.000
I guess how did they feel about the new buildings versus an actual integration in the school?

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:20.000
I think they were exuberant about the new building because the real stalwarts of education, I don't think pushed integration.

00:40:20.000 --> 00:40:34.000
I think they thought with equal footing, financing and resources, Roe and could be as good as had his burger.

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:52.000
I don't know that from those old warriors that they pushed and promoted desegregation from the perspective of we're happy to be integrated.

00:40:52.000 --> 00:41:10.000
I think they wanted the everyday attendance, money to be equal. I think they wanted new books and as opposed to one microscope in the biology lab to one per key as in other schools.

00:41:10.000 --> 00:41:24.000
I remember seeing one new textbook in the month of October or November in 1968 and that was a geometry book.

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:26.000
How did it sneak through?

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:44.000
Well, they didn't have any to send us. We always got our books from one of the other predominately Caucasian schools, but I'm sure they didn't have any anyway because obviously September passed in October 2, so we finally got new books.

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:52.000
You mentioned N.R. Burger, can you tell us about N.R. Burger?

00:41:52.000 --> 00:42:02.000
I think he was a visionary. Before his time.

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:06.000
What was his role in the community for people who don't know who he was?

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:14.000
He was an educator and principal at Eureka, Wall Street High, and Rowan High School.

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:33.000
And as I have said, there had to be a connection with him being so intellectual for the reason that he chose Cornell University to do graduate work as opposed to Brown or University of Missouri or Indiana like many others.

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:39.000
The current superintendent of public schools in Hattiesburg had gone to Cornell.

00:42:39.000 --> 00:42:48.000
And N.R. Burger mastered, if not the classes that Dr. Blair had.

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:55.000
And I think demonstrated that he was on par if not above and beyond his abilities.

00:42:55.000 --> 00:43:12.000
So I think the freedoms that N.R. Burger were allowed or given or took led him to build a school system in Hattiesburg second to none, though not integrated.

00:43:12.000 --> 00:43:18.000
And so you think it was a very deliberate choice on his part to go to the same institute?

00:43:18.000 --> 00:43:21.000
I think so.

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:35.000
You mentioned earlier that Hattiesburg was one of the few places in the state in the forties that had high school, 12th grade for African Americans.

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:39.000
What was the impact of being one of the few places that had that?

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:44.000
Well, the reason I had a conversation with N.R. Burger's son and others,

00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:59.000
that were people coming from a catchment area around 50 miles to live here if they had a house or bedroom available so that their kids could achieve a high school diploma.

00:43:59.000 --> 00:44:04.000
Otherwise, eighth, ninth grade would be the end of it.

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:16.000
Hattiesburg was just a feeder program to Alcorn State University since the lion's share of our educators were from Alcorn.

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:28.000
And I'm sure there were those that were Dr. N.R. Burger today and then I'm sure N.R. Burger were others to that.

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:33.000
You mentioned that your Alabama relatives were very interested in voter registration.

00:44:33.000 --> 00:44:36.000
Was your father, did your father try to register?

00:44:36.000 --> 00:44:38.000
My father never voted.

00:44:38.000 --> 00:44:43.000
I never was able to get him to vote.

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:55.000
Did he talk to you about why he didn't want to or wouldn't?

00:44:55.000 --> 00:45:09.000
I can't recall comments to that, but I think he valued his relationships with whites of power.

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:19.000
I think he didn't want to do anything where he would be seen as different.

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:25.000
And he would say things like, I'm paving away for you.

00:45:25.000 --> 00:45:28.000
And that he did.

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:45.000
I don't know of any way I went downtown as a 16, 17, 18 year old that some degree of openness didn't come to me as a result of a relationship that he had.

00:45:45.000 --> 00:45:48.000
And when you say downtown, that's the right thing.

00:45:48.000 --> 00:45:50.000
Correct.

00:45:50.000 --> 00:45:55.000
And so people there had an idea who you were because of your father?

00:45:55.000 --> 00:45:57.000
I think so to an extent.

00:45:57.000 --> 00:46:00.000
Which makes it a safer place for you.

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:02.000
Correct.

00:46:02.000 --> 00:46:10.000
I think I still had to earn my way, but I don't think I had to jump the thorned edges that many others.

00:46:10.000 --> 00:46:25.000
I don't think I would have to go through three tiers of screening as to allow me to buy a watch on credit because Willie Holloway had an account there.

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:41.000
Or to the service station or to the nurse, I mean, to the pharmacy or places of that kind.

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:43.000
Did you go downtown much?

00:46:43.000 --> 00:46:45.000
Yes.

00:46:45.000 --> 00:46:52.000
So there were things that you could get downtown that you couldn't get on Mobile Street?

00:46:52.000 --> 00:46:59.000
Oh, I mean, you had an account at Sears, JC Penney, Bill Whitley.

00:46:59.000 --> 00:47:11.000
I had accounts, my mother had accounts at various and sundry stores, bins, taillard shop, various other places that I would go with him.

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:13.000
So more selection.

00:47:13.000 --> 00:47:15.000
Correct.

00:47:15.000 --> 00:47:19.000
You mentioned that your mother had the beauty shop.

00:47:19.000 --> 00:47:23.000
Did you spend much time there when she was still living?

00:47:23.000 --> 00:47:30.000
Yes, for the most part, in there when she was dressing hair as they called it then.

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:33.000
Did you listen to the conversations?

00:47:33.000 --> 00:47:37.000
What was that like as a person?

00:47:37.000 --> 00:47:40.000
Yes.

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:49.000
At that time, children were not afforded the rights to linger.

00:47:49.000 --> 00:47:57.000
But how would pick up on snippets of hot topics?

00:47:57.000 --> 00:48:03.000
I talked to Ms. Conner the other day and she said that, actually I don't think she said it the other day,

00:48:03.000 --> 00:48:16.000
but I read it in the interview she had done that some of the civil rights workers were specifically trying to talk to beauticians and midwives and encourage them to join the movie.

00:48:16.000 --> 00:48:19.000
Do you know if anybody talked to your mother about that?

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:20.000
I don't recall that.

00:48:20.000 --> 00:48:23.000
And Ms. Conner lived three doors for me.

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:25.000
So I was in out of that house.

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:30.000
I was in effect, I just came from seeing her son in the cumolesson home Sunday.

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:32.000
So I came up in that house as well.

00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:33.000
Didn't Frank and I?

00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:35.000
Yes, so you roughly the same age?

00:48:35.000 --> 00:48:36.000
Same age?

00:48:36.000 --> 00:48:40.000
I think 15, 20 days apart.

00:48:40.000 --> 00:48:41.000
Wow.

00:48:41.000 --> 00:48:42.000
It's almost like a twin brother.

00:48:42.000 --> 00:48:43.000
Correct.

00:48:43.000 --> 00:48:52.000
Did any of your teachers talk about voting in the regular schools?

00:48:53.000 --> 00:49:15.000
Only when I got to the 9th or 10th grade, Ms. Berger, Ms. Sandefa, N.R. Burger, Mr. Clarence McGee, those were topics of voting at that time.

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:18.000
So they would encourage students to register.

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:20.000
When you were of age?

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:23.000
Yeah, we weren't of age at that time.

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:28.000
But topics of voting were discussed in class.

00:49:28.000 --> 00:49:36.000
Do you know if that was part of the formal curriculum or is that they're taking liberties to do that?

00:49:36.000 --> 00:49:46.000
I would think there would have been more liberties than courses on civics.

00:49:46.000 --> 00:49:54.000
Of course, they have that now, but my understanding is that it was a taboo subject according to the white student attendance.

00:49:54.000 --> 00:49:55.000
Right.

00:49:55.000 --> 00:50:09.000
And in the book, Count them one by one, which is in a count of the voting rights efforts in Hattiesburg.

00:50:09.000 --> 00:50:16.000
Yes, out of Boston, yes.

00:50:16.000 --> 00:50:23.000
I'm sorry, I missed what you were saying about the book.

00:50:23.000 --> 00:50:24.000
Yes.

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:34.000
I'm just saying that at that era, that era in time, Theron Lynd was a discussion all over the city of Hattiesburg.

00:50:34.000 --> 00:50:41.000
People talking from time to time, and it's centered on African-Americans voting.

00:50:41.000 --> 00:50:51.000
But even prior to that, there were a group of 15 and more that attempted to vote.

00:50:51.000 --> 00:50:54.000
So you remember those conversations in the community about that?

00:50:54.000 --> 00:50:55.000
Oh, certainly, yes.

00:50:55.000 --> 00:50:56.000
Oh, certainly, yes.

00:50:56.000 --> 00:51:02.000
What did you think about it?

00:51:02.000 --> 00:51:07.000
I accepted that Black folk couldn't vote.

00:51:07.000 --> 00:51:14.000
I accepted that there were separate facilities.

00:51:14.000 --> 00:51:21.000
I didn't accept that that would be permanent, but I accepted that that was the status quo.

00:51:21.000 --> 00:51:28.000
I accepted that that would be those that would agree to that.

00:51:28.000 --> 00:51:33.000
But I knew that that wouldn't be permanent.

00:51:33.000 --> 00:51:39.000
That in time, things would change.

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:43.000
What's your first memory of race?

00:51:43.000 --> 00:51:50.000
Of an understanding of sort of the rules of white supremacy?

00:51:59.000 --> 00:52:03.000
I don't know of the first.

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:27.000
I remember of a consciousness of being invited to USM to attend a quasi-student council, something, something of students, and being the only African-American president.

00:52:27.000 --> 00:52:35.000
There has never been an account or time that I can't recall that I was Black or different.

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:40.000
I was always, I mean, my folk in Alabama made me aware of that.

00:52:40.000 --> 00:52:43.000
Did you always remember that?

00:52:43.000 --> 00:52:49.000
This is the way you act as a result of that consciousness.

00:52:49.000 --> 00:53:01.000
But probably sitting in that meeting, I remember it was hot in the head on a wall, cool.

00:53:01.000 --> 00:53:05.000
That was the only good I had.

00:53:05.000 --> 00:53:09.000
I remember saying one day I'd go out to wear this wall, cool.

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:12.000
In me.

00:53:12.000 --> 00:53:15.000
In Mississippi.

00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:29.000
I've always, if there's any gift that I've had, and I say this without ego, I think I've always thought of possibilities.

00:53:29.000 --> 00:53:46.000
And I've always thought of reframing a situation, despite the current circumstances of it, that there would be, there's a way out of this.

00:53:46.000 --> 00:54:05.000
And I remember reading that you're successful if you've got six payments of your salary in a man-made jaw in the bank.

00:54:06.000 --> 00:54:08.000
Can we?

00:54:08.000 --> 00:54:15.000
And old have I felt so fortunate since I've been dead.

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:18.000
Do you have it in the man-made jaw?

00:54:18.000 --> 00:54:22.000
A little bit.

00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:26.000
Keep it handy, right?

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:32.000
What are the first civil rights activities that you remember in Hadestburg?

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:36.000
The marches and the mass meetings.

00:54:36.000 --> 00:55:01.000
They were almost nightly mass meetings from true light Baptist Church to St. Paul, to Mount Zion, Baptist Church to Palmer's Cross and the marches.

00:55:01.000 --> 00:55:04.000
I attend the meetings.

00:55:04.000 --> 00:55:21.000
But again, as young, one of the luxuries, if you will, was after my mom's death, being able to go fairly freely.

00:55:21.000 --> 00:55:29.000
Well, you were just going to be at home. My mom would go at the, go on the back porch around.

00:55:29.000 --> 00:55:34.000
Because she'd had to be five minutes to six or something, but she would whistle.

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:39.000
And I mean, you can hear two, three blocks away. That was your signal?

00:55:39.000 --> 00:55:41.000
Let's get home.

00:55:41.000 --> 00:55:46.000
Or certainly, the street light didn't catch you away from the house.

00:55:46.000 --> 00:55:50.000
She was a strong-wield person.

00:55:50.000 --> 00:55:53.000
I say that they did all the way with kids.

00:55:53.000 --> 00:55:57.000
I needed my mom for about ten minutes.

00:55:57.000 --> 00:56:01.000
I didn't need a police officer just my mom.

00:56:01.000 --> 00:56:07.000
So after she passed, then I was able to go to some of the mass meetings.

00:56:07.000 --> 00:56:12.000
But not caught blocked. I mean, I had to be back here in the day 39.

00:56:12.000 --> 00:56:17.000
Or there would be a responsible person who, it's my dad, would let me go with.

00:56:17.000 --> 00:56:26.000
And one of those summers, relatives came from Muskegon, Michigan.

00:56:26.000 --> 00:56:34.000
And they were down and I had probably more leverage, more fun, more freedom than I ever had.

00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:38.000
I'm guessing your dad didn't go there.

00:56:38.000 --> 00:56:41.000
No, my dad didn't go.

00:56:41.000 --> 00:56:48.000
What were the meetings like to you?

00:56:48.000 --> 00:57:00.000
It would have been the first time I'd been in an integrated meetings with whites.

00:57:00.000 --> 00:57:07.000
It reflected to me hope and freedom.

00:57:07.000 --> 00:57:23.000
You know how they said they trained elephants and at babies they put chains around one of the feet.

00:57:23.000 --> 00:57:34.000
But over time after they are inculcated into that mindset that the chain turns into a small string.

00:57:34.000 --> 00:57:37.000
It's a mindset.

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:49.000
Well, just hearing that the freedom writers, and just the name, they were freedom writers that they were coming to set us free.

00:57:49.000 --> 00:57:56.000
But I have to say this.

00:57:56.000 --> 00:58:05.000
My dad, despite his hesitancy, to be involved in what we call the civil rights movement,

00:58:05.000 --> 00:58:18.000
he never spoke to me in terms of, I had limits of achievement.

00:58:18.000 --> 00:58:24.000
I mean, he never said, I wanted to go to Haddishburg High School.

00:58:24.000 --> 00:58:37.000
And Miss Conninson, Danny Went, my kids, Jeffrey and Taney, that I lived without the mom died when, not of them went.

00:58:37.000 --> 00:58:38.000
I wanted to go.

00:58:38.000 --> 00:58:50.000
And my dad said, baby, let me ask Miss Eddowne, she was a white lady, that man is the office at the fertilizer place.

00:58:50.000 --> 00:58:55.000
Now until this day I don't know whether he lied or not.

00:58:55.000 --> 00:58:57.000
But I couldn't wait until he got back home.

00:58:57.000 --> 00:59:02.000
I said, Dan, what did he say?

00:59:03.000 --> 00:59:11.000
He said, she said, things are going well, where you are, you need to stay there.

00:59:11.000 --> 00:59:15.000
I can't discount that.

00:59:15.000 --> 00:59:22.000
But I know I couldn't have been more happier than being at Rowan High School.

00:59:22.000 --> 00:59:29.000
I don't think, because Danny came back, Jeffrey came back, Jesse came back,

00:59:29.000 --> 00:59:45.000
all those that I know went, came back and didn't graduate of Field, or face some kind of challenge.

00:59:45.000 --> 00:59:50.000
Were you disappointed when you said that?

00:59:50.000 --> 00:59:59.000
And so when you say, now, today you couldn't have been happier than you were at Roe and is that in retrospect, did you have some sense of that even at the time?

00:59:59.000 --> 01:00:11.000
I don't think I would have had to pride that Rowan High School was pride.

01:00:11.000 --> 01:00:16.000
Give a man a fish, he'll eat today.

01:00:16.000 --> 01:00:20.000
Teach a man to fish, he'll eat for a lifetime.

01:00:20.000 --> 01:00:24.000
That's what those folks would take that stage every day and tell you.

01:00:24.000 --> 01:00:29.000
He who knows and knows not that he knows not, he needs to be taught.

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:32.000
I wouldn't have gotten all of that.

01:00:32.000 --> 01:00:40.000
I wouldn't have gotten, you know, I look at Danny, I look at all those others, I'm not naked.

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:43.000
I'm not negative to them.

01:00:43.000 --> 01:00:48.000
But that was what I needed, where I was.

01:00:48.000 --> 01:00:57.000
So if Miss Edner made that decision, or if my daddy made that decision, that was the right decision for Eddie Holloway.

01:00:57.000 --> 01:01:09.000
You said that you mentioned Danny and others who went, transferred, and this is, I assume freedom of choice, to the White School, had his bird house.

01:01:09.000 --> 01:01:16.000
And that all the ones you know came back to the Black Schools.

01:01:16.000 --> 01:01:22.000
Well, let me say not all, but a significant number for whatever reason.

01:01:22.000 --> 01:01:26.000
Did they talk to you about why they came back?

01:01:26.000 --> 01:01:38.000
No. But even today as we get together, as in reunions, those that went to Hadisbury High.

01:01:38.000 --> 01:01:46.000
For whatever reason, still come to our reunion.

01:01:46.000 --> 01:01:48.000
Why?

01:01:48.000 --> 01:01:51.000
I've never been man enough to ask.

01:01:51.000 --> 01:01:53.000
Why don't you go to your own reunion?

01:01:53.000 --> 01:01:54.000
I've never been there.

01:01:54.000 --> 01:01:57.000
But there was something, there's something.

01:01:57.000 --> 01:01:59.000
Does that make sense?

01:01:59.000 --> 01:02:03.000
We just had a gathering, this past summer, all of them came.

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:07.000
And I wanted to say, well, you didn't go to school.

01:02:07.000 --> 01:02:09.000
I'm a union graduate with us.

01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:13.000
But I never, I wouldn't have seen it.

01:02:13.000 --> 01:02:21.000
The children who transferred over there, do you know what their motive, did they make that decision?

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:23.000
Did parents make that decision?

01:02:23.000 --> 01:02:25.000
I think in part their parents.

01:02:25.000 --> 01:02:29.000
I think they thought the grants was greater.

01:02:29.000 --> 01:02:34.000
The water was colder.

01:02:34.000 --> 01:02:47.000
And they may have gotten better, pitty-go-gy, but not love, understanding, a third eye or a third eye.

01:02:47.000 --> 01:02:50.000
I can assure you that.

01:02:50.000 --> 01:02:56.000
Do you think any of them, any of the parents, just thought somebody had to do it?

01:02:56.000 --> 01:02:58.000
Do you think they really thought it was better or they did?

01:02:58.000 --> 01:03:00.000
Well, I think they thought it was better.

01:03:00.000 --> 01:03:01.000
I think by far.

01:03:01.000 --> 01:03:04.000
I think many parents thought it was better.

01:03:04.000 --> 01:03:06.000
Because I heard them say.

01:03:06.000 --> 01:03:12.000
Is that because the equipment, because it's white, is it the resources at the schools?

01:03:12.000 --> 01:03:13.000
I think all of them.

01:03:13.000 --> 01:03:16.000
All of the above.

01:03:16.000 --> 01:03:23.000
And I think I asked you this already, but I'll ask it again.

01:03:23.000 --> 01:03:27.000
Did they talk to you about the kind of harassment that they experienced in those schools?

01:03:27.000 --> 01:03:37.000
I've heard just a conglomerate of things like that.

01:03:37.000 --> 01:03:44.000
I have to believe it because they say it.

01:03:44.000 --> 01:03:51.000
But I never experienced that in my life.

01:03:52.000 --> 01:03:56.000
I was the first student out here as a resident assistant.

01:03:56.000 --> 01:04:02.000
I was the first student of color as an officer assistant.

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:04.000
And I don't say this with ego.

01:04:04.000 --> 01:04:12.000
I was the first to staff, Elam Arms, which was an upscale, 455.

01:04:12.000 --> 01:04:24.000
Mill Residents' house that was home that was private, swimming pool, turned back service, food catered by.

01:04:24.000 --> 01:04:30.000
Morrison's.

01:04:30.000 --> 01:04:33.000
I've never experienced that.

01:04:33.000 --> 01:04:35.000
What year did you come out here?

01:04:35.000 --> 01:04:41.000
In the 1960s, Washington, DC, right in that building.

01:04:41.000 --> 01:04:44.000
How did you get that job?

01:04:44.000 --> 01:04:50.000
I was standing on the corner and I asked the man, do you know where I could find work?

01:04:50.000 --> 01:04:54.000
And he called me a little and that even.

01:04:54.000 --> 01:04:55.000
You were in high school then?

01:04:55.000 --> 01:04:56.000
Yes.

01:04:56.000 --> 01:04:59.000
Was this during the school year or summer job?

01:04:59.000 --> 01:05:00.000
Summer.

01:05:00.000 --> 01:05:01.000
Summer?

01:05:02.000 --> 01:05:09.000
What was it like to work over here doing working in the kitchen?

01:05:09.000 --> 01:05:12.000
I mean, it was washing dishes.

01:05:12.000 --> 01:05:16.000
I had washed dishes at southern air hotel.

01:05:16.000 --> 01:05:19.000
I had washed dishes at the grease from the hotel.

01:05:19.000 --> 01:05:21.000
So, washing dishes?

01:05:21.000 --> 01:05:26.000
And so, I'm assuming all of the black workers, all the workers, wrapped in American in the kitchen?

01:05:26.000 --> 01:05:27.000
Yes.

01:05:28.000 --> 01:05:31.000
So, were there people you moved by the community?

01:05:31.000 --> 01:05:32.000
Unuming.

01:05:32.000 --> 01:05:33.000
Unuming.

01:05:33.000 --> 01:05:38.000
You said that you were the first resident assistant.

01:05:38.000 --> 01:05:40.000
What year did you come out here to school?

01:05:40.000 --> 01:05:41.000
1970.

01:05:41.000 --> 01:05:47.000
Did it make a difference to you coming here to school that you had actually already worked on campus?

01:05:47.000 --> 01:05:48.000
No.

01:05:48.000 --> 01:05:56.000
Actually, Miss Sip and N.R. Burger and all of those that I just, that I have referenced.

01:05:57.000 --> 01:06:01.000
They wanted me to go to Jackson State All-Core.

01:06:01.000 --> 01:06:14.000
My choice to go to USM was because of my father was living and I needed to be somewhere where I could hate an assistant.

01:06:14.000 --> 01:06:17.000
My dad remarried.

01:06:17.000 --> 01:06:20.000
Over you, my dad?

01:06:20.000 --> 01:06:21.000
15.

01:06:22.000 --> 01:06:24.000
Okay, well, that.

01:06:24.000 --> 01:06:27.000
You enrolled out here at Southern in 1970.

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:31.000
That's about five years after the first African American go on campus?

01:06:31.000 --> 01:06:32.000
Correct.

01:06:32.000 --> 01:06:35.000
Because I was okay.

01:06:35.000 --> 01:06:39.000
And I believe you said that you moved both of the young women who were...

01:06:39.000 --> 01:06:46.000
They came to our mother's, a beautiful and their mother's and grandmother's did.

01:06:46.000 --> 01:06:51.000
Did you have an opportunity to talk to them about their experiences before you came out?

01:06:51.000 --> 01:06:53.000
We sung in the church choir.

01:06:53.000 --> 01:06:54.000
Yeah, yeah.

01:06:54.000 --> 01:06:59.000
What did they say about it?

01:06:59.000 --> 01:07:04.000
I never had direct conversation with them other than...

01:07:04.000 --> 01:07:08.000
I would say that Elaine, I'm strong and I were relatively close.

01:07:08.000 --> 01:07:11.000
Miss Branch was an older person.

01:07:11.000 --> 01:07:16.000
So she was fairly really remote to the fiber of the school.

01:07:16.000 --> 01:07:31.000
Elaine lived on campus, sung in the choir, traveled with the team, the choir in Mexico, the whole world.

01:07:32.000 --> 01:07:41.000
So, I don't think I need an explanation.

01:07:41.000 --> 01:07:45.000
I was fairly independent at that time.

01:07:45.000 --> 01:07:57.000
I remember taking a bus, getting off the bus out here, taking off school that day, letting the council know I was going to be out, coming out here, applying for school,

01:07:57.000 --> 01:08:06.000
to take the ACT test and kind of that's the rest of that was history and I said if I didn't make...

01:08:06.000 --> 01:08:15.000
If I were not admitted, I'd try William Carey or...

01:08:16.000 --> 01:08:32.000
So I had probably had at that time met a couple of people that worked during the summer's own recreational facilities and they were students of USM.

01:08:32.000 --> 01:08:35.000
They would have been graduate students.

01:08:35.000 --> 01:08:38.000
Are these whites there?

01:08:38.000 --> 01:08:39.000
Yes.

01:08:40.000 --> 01:08:46.000
Any more good relationships with them?

01:08:46.000 --> 01:08:55.000
I cannot sit here and tell you of walls that have here with White Folk.

01:08:56.000 --> 01:09:01.000
I put my plan for the Resonance Assistance job.

01:09:01.000 --> 01:09:07.000
They moved me for room 33364, Scott Hall, to 411.

01:09:07.000 --> 01:09:16.000
I asked, why were you moving me and they said, you're planning for a Resonance Assistance job?

01:09:16.000 --> 01:09:18.000
I said, yes.

01:09:18.000 --> 01:09:23.000
They said, we don't have one at this time, but see if you'd like it.

01:09:23.000 --> 01:09:35.000
I mean, I think I was insightful enough to know that they were putting me on 411 because it was an all-white floor and to see if I could relate to White Kids.

01:09:36.000 --> 01:09:40.000
And those guys became my best friend.

01:09:40.000 --> 01:09:54.000
Edward Wong and all those guys and the next year they offered me the head residency for the entire hall.

01:09:54.000 --> 01:09:59.000
So were you in R.A. that year when you moved here?

01:09:59.000 --> 01:10:01.000
Without pay.

01:10:02.000 --> 01:10:04.000
So you did a year of voluntary R.A.

01:10:04.000 --> 01:10:05.000
And then you came here?

01:10:05.000 --> 01:10:13.000
Didn't like it that it was volunteer, but knew that it was a pathway and a stepping stone that my day would come.

01:10:13.000 --> 01:10:20.000
So you lived on campus, even when you were in the office to stay in town to be near your dad?

01:10:20.000 --> 01:10:21.000
Yes.

01:10:21.000 --> 01:10:23.000
What made you decide to live on campus?

01:10:23.000 --> 01:10:25.000
Well, I could get my meals.

01:10:25.000 --> 01:10:26.000
Okay.

01:10:26.000 --> 01:10:28.000
And I didn't have a car.

01:10:28.000 --> 01:10:31.000
It was a lot easier to be on campus.

01:10:31.000 --> 01:10:32.000
Correct.

01:10:32.000 --> 01:10:39.000
So one of the things we sort of have skipped is the Freedom Schools.

01:10:39.000 --> 01:10:40.000
Yes.

01:10:40.000 --> 01:10:42.000
How did you get involved in the field school?

01:10:42.000 --> 01:10:55.000
Well, all up and down, we'll be a street where freedom libraries around at that time it was called the Black folks Library.

01:10:55.000 --> 01:10:58.000
It was really the community center.

01:10:58.000 --> 01:11:00.000
There were Freedom School efforts.

01:11:00.000 --> 01:11:14.000
And then there were Freedom School efforts at the True Light Baptist Church.

01:11:14.000 --> 01:11:24.000
I would go for not every day.

01:11:24.000 --> 01:11:30.000
I'd go and get a book from the library.

01:11:30.000 --> 01:11:42.000
I would go to some of the meetings.

01:11:42.000 --> 01:11:50.000
But the old folk in Alabama,

01:11:50.000 --> 01:12:03.000
they really instilled in me a sense and response mindset.

01:12:03.000 --> 01:12:12.000
I remember going, I've never told this.

01:12:12.000 --> 01:12:17.000
But many of those kids appeared to be just a maciated impoverty.

01:12:17.000 --> 01:12:23.000
They are parents.

01:12:23.000 --> 01:12:42.000
They are a sense of without a lack of knowing of where they were.

01:12:42.000 --> 01:12:49.000
Being driven there because they were going to give them some food.

01:12:49.000 --> 01:12:52.000
And so I was going to tell them,

01:12:52.000 --> 01:12:57.000
they weren't trying to either to lose or talk me against it.

01:12:57.000 --> 01:13:01.000
They said, go buy your own belongings.

01:13:01.000 --> 01:13:06.000
And don't even be real unless you touch the dollar.

01:13:06.000 --> 01:13:11.000
So I didn't participate like the other students who would participate.

01:13:11.000 --> 01:13:15.000
Many of those that participated, that parents were involved.

01:13:15.000 --> 01:13:20.000
But I knew to go get me a couple of books.

01:13:20.000 --> 01:13:28.000
I knew to read the encyclopedias of different things like that.

01:13:28.000 --> 01:13:33.000
But I didn't do a lot of that stuff.

01:13:33.000 --> 01:13:39.000
I marched.

01:13:39.000 --> 01:13:45.000
When I was since danger, I would leave.

01:13:45.000 --> 01:13:52.000
If we were marching one night up town and we get there,

01:13:52.000 --> 01:13:57.000
and I see people that represented the clans with guns.

01:13:57.000 --> 01:14:00.000
And I knew all the other guys with me on there,

01:14:00.000 --> 01:14:03.000
a couple of bottles, broken a beer bottle.

01:14:03.000 --> 01:14:06.000
I'd go home.

01:14:06.000 --> 01:14:16.000
I don't want to say I was an outlier.

01:14:16.000 --> 01:14:19.000
But as long as I can remember,

01:14:19.000 --> 01:14:23.000
I've been an independent thinker.

01:14:23.000 --> 01:14:29.000
I hope that's best to describe it that way.

01:14:29.000 --> 01:14:32.000
Sounds like it.

01:14:32.000 --> 01:14:38.000
Did you ever sit in classes?

01:14:38.000 --> 01:14:41.000
Did you ever participate?

01:14:41.000 --> 01:14:46.000
Not just the library, violin, or books, but the three-year school classes.

01:14:46.000 --> 01:14:53.000
Yeah, I would go when they were talking about civility, civics.

01:14:53.000 --> 01:14:56.000
I would go sometimes when those people,

01:14:56.000 --> 01:15:01.000
they would bring in guitarists and they'd play.

01:15:01.000 --> 01:15:07.000
But I didn't go at...

01:15:07.000 --> 01:15:10.000
I think I got the essence.

01:15:10.000 --> 01:15:13.000
I would go around with some of the people knocking on doors

01:15:13.000 --> 01:15:21.000
and asking them what they registered to vote.

01:15:21.000 --> 01:15:25.000
I would like to say that my environment was kind of structured,

01:15:25.000 --> 01:15:26.000
if you will.

01:15:26.000 --> 01:15:29.000
Does that make sense?

01:15:29.000 --> 01:15:32.000
Do you remember how people would respond

01:15:32.000 --> 01:15:38.000
or how you felt when you were doing the canvassing on board?

01:15:38.000 --> 01:15:46.000
A preparation for that was how my dad saw it.

01:15:46.000 --> 01:15:55.000
He didn't want any part of it.

01:15:55.000 --> 01:16:05.000
Though he was not oblivious to the issues of race,

01:16:05.000 --> 01:16:08.000
he may have seen himself beyond that.

01:16:08.000 --> 01:16:10.000
I don't know who he'd ever discussed it.

01:16:10.000 --> 01:16:14.000
But I always said,

01:16:14.000 --> 01:16:16.000
what's the benefit of this?

01:16:16.000 --> 01:16:18.000
What's the benefit of that?

01:16:18.000 --> 01:16:21.000
How might it impact the masses?

01:16:21.000 --> 01:16:25.000
So I would be prone to, if I'd go to the doctor,

01:16:25.000 --> 01:16:28.000
Dr. A. T. Tatum's office,

01:16:28.000 --> 01:16:29.000
and they'd turn,

01:16:29.000 --> 01:16:31.000
so you have to go to the back door,

01:16:31.000 --> 01:16:32.000
and I would say no,

01:16:32.000 --> 01:16:35.000
I'd like to go to the front door.

01:16:35.000 --> 01:16:37.000
What's your response?

01:16:37.000 --> 01:16:40.000
Well, they asked me out.

01:16:40.000 --> 01:16:46.000
So I'd call the Office of Civil Rights in DC.

01:16:46.000 --> 01:16:49.000
And Dr. Tatum called me and said,

01:16:49.000 --> 01:16:54.000
He'll be your grandmother and my arms at the time of her death.

01:16:54.000 --> 01:16:58.000
I've known your daddy best,

01:16:58.000 --> 01:16:59.000
man, I know.

01:16:59.000 --> 01:17:05.000
But you can't come back to my office.

01:17:05.000 --> 01:17:11.000
From that point on,

01:17:11.000 --> 01:17:14.000
I don't know what I was a snitch for the government.

01:17:14.000 --> 01:17:16.000
I probably never told this either,

01:17:16.000 --> 01:17:25.000
But I receive calls from the Office of Civil Rights for 25 years on voting, location changes,

01:17:25.000 --> 01:17:34.320
on my opinions on anything changing the boundaries from schools and things that I can.

01:17:34.320 --> 01:17:51.440
So quietly I filed objections to separate medical facilities over around the old

01:17:51.440 --> 01:17:55.680
Methodist Hospital and Petal Mississippi.

01:17:55.680 --> 01:18:07.680
I know that one of the things that civil rights act and then I can't remember what the name of the legislation was that provided more federal funding for medical facilities.

01:18:07.680 --> 01:18:15.680
But what both of those did was provide this kind of recourse right where there's Petal over oversight.

01:18:15.680 --> 01:18:20.680
When you had that encounter with the doctor, is that like the late 70s?

01:18:20.680 --> 01:18:23.680
I mean late 60s, early 70s.

01:18:23.680 --> 01:18:35.680
Now what they did was they locked the door from entrance but you would have to go through the front and go back to the same room.

01:18:35.680 --> 01:18:45.680
And I remember really being bothered by my dad still went to him.

01:18:45.680 --> 01:18:54.680
His sister still went to him and all of those teachers that lived across the street that I taught still went to him.

01:18:54.680 --> 01:18:59.680
And I remember that as almost overwhelming.

01:18:59.680 --> 01:19:02.680
So they were going to the White Doctor and said the Dr. Schmerk?

01:19:02.680 --> 01:19:07.680
Yes. They were going to Dr. Tatum, AT Tatum.

01:19:07.680 --> 01:19:10.680
And they were going that front door and going back to that pack.

01:19:10.680 --> 01:19:12.680
Do you know why they would see him?

01:19:12.680 --> 01:19:15.680
I'm sure family lineage.

01:19:15.680 --> 01:19:21.680
It made me also heal out pay if they didn't have insurance.

01:19:21.680 --> 01:19:26.680
I think he really think he was a quality physician.

01:19:26.680 --> 01:19:28.680
Good strong track record.

01:19:28.680 --> 01:19:34.680
Probably have more African American clients than otherwise.

01:19:34.680 --> 01:19:40.680
I never saw anything ill about his services.

01:19:40.680 --> 01:19:44.680
Do you have any idea how he would answer?

01:19:44.680 --> 01:19:46.680
I mean I'm asking you how he would answer.

01:19:46.680 --> 01:19:50.680
But you know he's saying to you, I held your grandmother once she was dying.

01:19:50.680 --> 01:19:52.680
There's so much intimacy in that.

01:19:52.680 --> 01:19:54.680
I mean that's a very intimate thing.

01:19:54.680 --> 01:19:57.680
And yet you can't walk in the front door.

01:19:57.680 --> 01:20:03.680
Well my conversation with him is that I remember like it was yesterday.

01:20:03.680 --> 01:20:08.680
I said Dr. Tatum.

01:20:08.680 --> 01:20:12.680
I share seats with your daughter.

01:20:12.680 --> 01:20:18.680
And we today are in a political science class.

01:20:18.680 --> 01:20:21.680
And we enter the same door.

01:20:21.680 --> 01:20:26.680
Her name is Nancy and my name is Eddie.

01:20:26.680 --> 01:20:31.680
And she's such a nice person.

01:20:31.680 --> 01:20:33.680
So we beat it.

01:20:33.680 --> 01:20:37.680
I didn't do that without fear.

01:20:37.680 --> 01:20:46.680
At that time I was, I managed the front desk of Scott Hall.

01:20:46.680 --> 01:20:54.680
And I had access to master keys for all of the rooms and all of the halls.

01:20:54.680 --> 01:21:00.680
So I would stay in various and sundry rooms at night in fear.

01:21:00.680 --> 01:21:04.680
And it may have been a false fear.

01:21:04.680 --> 01:21:08.680
That's a lot of access for you to have had.

01:21:08.680 --> 01:21:12.680
To be able to get in all the rooms.

01:21:12.680 --> 01:21:15.680
That was not public.

01:21:15.680 --> 01:21:20.680
Only because I worked in the front desk.

01:21:20.680 --> 01:21:23.680
Do you remember other incidents like that?

01:21:23.680 --> 01:21:25.680
Or challenging those boundaries?

01:21:25.680 --> 01:21:27.680
I've always challenged boundaries.

01:21:27.680 --> 01:21:29.680
I've always applied.

01:21:29.680 --> 01:21:31.680
I always asked for what reason.

01:21:31.680 --> 01:21:38.680
I've always thought that if I could equate the other applicants at some point in time.

01:21:38.680 --> 01:21:44.680
I'm sure to some extent I would rationalize it as providential if I didn't get it.

01:21:44.680 --> 01:21:46.680
The next man wheel.

01:21:46.680 --> 01:21:51.680
At least I opened the door.

01:21:51.680 --> 01:21:58.680
I applied for a scholarship if you will.

01:21:58.680 --> 01:22:06.680
A specialized service training of your choice to help you in provisional conditions.

01:22:06.680 --> 01:22:10.680
I can't recall the name of that scholarship.

01:22:10.680 --> 01:22:13.680
But anyway, I made it to the third round of that.

01:22:13.680 --> 01:22:17.680
I had to go to the Sheridan Hotel in Jackson.

01:22:17.680 --> 01:22:24.680
And it was new for an African American back then.

01:22:25.680 --> 01:22:27.680
I always wanted to be.

01:22:27.680 --> 01:22:35.680
My day would always say, you can't be juged up on wife up around wife of all the time.

01:22:35.680 --> 01:22:40.680
But I didn't desire to be jugged up on the wife.

01:22:40.680 --> 01:22:43.680
I just desire access too.

01:22:43.680 --> 01:22:50.680
But during that interview, the guy said, Mr. Holloway, how are you?

01:22:51.680 --> 01:22:56.680
I see you're from Mississippi.

01:22:56.680 --> 01:23:00.680
What do you think of this? What do you think of that? What do you think of this?

01:23:00.680 --> 01:23:04.680
Do you know James O. Eastland? James O. Eastland?

01:23:04.680 --> 01:23:06.680
I say, yes, he's a senator.

01:23:06.680 --> 01:23:12.680
He says, what do you think about his service?

01:23:12.680 --> 01:23:19.680
I said, well, he's one of two senators, state of Mississippi, John C. Stennis,

01:23:19.680 --> 01:23:22.680
and Mr. Eastler.

01:23:22.680 --> 01:23:25.680
How do you think of his service?

01:23:25.680 --> 01:23:30.680
I say, I think he's an able service provider.

01:23:30.680 --> 01:23:31.680
You're the best, right?

01:23:31.680 --> 01:23:36.680
I'm doing my best and whatever, whatever.

01:23:36.680 --> 01:23:40.680
He said, I don't think much of it.

01:23:40.680 --> 01:23:43.680
And I said, okay.

01:23:43.680 --> 01:23:47.680
He says, you know, he offered the Farm Subsidy's Act.

01:23:47.680 --> 01:23:54.680
He said, what about farmers are paid not to grow crops?

01:23:54.680 --> 01:23:57.680
And he had, I say, I know what you're talking about.

01:23:57.680 --> 01:24:01.680
I say, he had enough land, he had to master to make 10 farms,

01:24:01.680 --> 01:24:06.680
and he was able to develop wealth from that.

01:24:06.680 --> 01:24:09.680
And he said, do you know something else?

01:24:09.680 --> 01:24:11.680
I say, yes.

01:24:11.680 --> 01:24:17.680
Sir, you're not going to be awarded this scholarship

01:24:17.680 --> 01:24:22.680
because you said that knowing what you just told me,

01:24:22.680 --> 01:24:36.680
and you accommodated me, leaders, walk a weary limb out with.

01:24:36.680 --> 01:24:40.680
What did you make of that?

01:24:40.680 --> 01:24:48.680
That they are places where you've got to take risks and tell the truth.

01:24:48.680 --> 01:24:50.680
So did you apply that lesson?

01:24:50.680 --> 01:24:53.680
Ever since then.

01:24:53.680 --> 01:24:59.680
I've learned to frame and reframe and do it in a way that it's accommodated

01:24:59.680 --> 01:25:05.680
and not so abrupt that it'll take me out of the formula.

01:25:05.680 --> 01:25:10.680
I think I've got that line of how to say your piece but do it in a way

01:25:10.680 --> 01:25:13.680
that somebody might put it here.

01:25:13.680 --> 01:25:19.680
You talked to me earlier about, you thought that N.R. Burger was really a visionary.

01:25:19.680 --> 01:25:24.680
Can you talk about, I think we mostly talked about that outside,

01:25:24.680 --> 01:25:26.680
and that on the interview.

01:25:26.680 --> 01:25:30.680
Can you talk about his role in the community?

01:25:30.680 --> 01:25:38.680
Did you talk on the table about his going to Cornell?

01:25:38.680 --> 01:25:46.680
I think N.R. Burger was a difficult walk.

01:25:46.680 --> 01:25:50.680
It was required that he remain on the inside,

01:25:50.680 --> 01:25:57.680
but he was conscious of those things that were paramount to the outside.

01:25:57.680 --> 01:26:06.680
A great debate that's under the surface now is his role or his inactivity

01:26:06.680 --> 01:26:13.680
or whether he had a role in Clyde Kennard effort to come here.

01:26:13.680 --> 01:26:17.680
I'm not sure.

01:26:17.680 --> 01:26:19.680
I've asked Dr. Lucas.

01:26:19.680 --> 01:26:26.680
I've asked Vernon's son, Vernon Dahmer's son.

01:26:26.680 --> 01:26:31.680
I've asked as many the older leaders as possible.

01:26:31.680 --> 01:26:42.680
I've heard that since the opposition was so strong for

01:26:42.680 --> 01:26:45.680
Clyde Kennard to come here,

01:26:45.680 --> 01:26:51.680
then a group of people say it will work to keep Clack out

01:26:51.680 --> 01:26:56.680
of the state if you'll finance a junior college and let it be on the financial

01:26:56.680 --> 01:26:59.680
adults of the state.

01:26:59.680 --> 01:27:01.680
That's a lofty.

01:27:01.680 --> 01:27:03.680
That's in perpetuity.

01:27:03.680 --> 01:27:06.680
You create a college.

01:27:06.680 --> 01:27:10.680
You pay that step for a while.

01:27:10.680 --> 01:27:14.680
That seems like the creation of a Berger,

01:27:14.680 --> 01:27:18.680
because it would have been Princess to two.

01:27:18.680 --> 01:27:23.680
The junior college is now defunded.

01:27:23.680 --> 01:27:25.680
That's where he came from.

01:27:25.680 --> 01:27:30.680
He lived there, where he's from.

01:27:30.680 --> 01:27:35.680
The hallmark of African-American education was in that

01:27:35.680 --> 01:27:44.680
printed support Gibson area.

01:27:44.680 --> 01:27:51.680
N.R. Burger was always in a negotiating posture.

01:27:51.680 --> 01:27:57.680
He was always leading in chaos.

01:27:57.680 --> 01:28:03.680
So the end product of his work was a stellar, separate,

01:28:03.680 --> 01:28:08.680
but almost equal educational system,

01:28:08.680 --> 01:28:15.680
where the average daily attendance and cost per key was significantly less than any other.

01:28:15.680 --> 01:28:21.680
So I hold him in high regard, just knowing the little that I know.

01:28:21.680 --> 01:28:26.680
But he was able to accomplish his context of his system.

01:28:26.680 --> 01:28:30.680
You mentioned Mr. Lucas and asking Mr. Lucas,

01:28:30.680 --> 01:28:32.680
is it Aubrey?

01:28:32.680 --> 01:28:33.680
Yes.

01:28:33.680 --> 01:28:35.680
And he was the registrar at the time.

01:28:35.680 --> 01:28:36.680
Yes.

01:28:36.680 --> 01:28:41.680
As he talked about what happened when Mr. Clyde Kennard tried to come out here.

01:28:41.680 --> 01:28:45.680
He told me that,

01:28:45.680 --> 01:28:52.680
any at the time N.R. Burger spoke with legislators

01:28:52.680 --> 01:28:54.680
and the wealthy,

01:28:54.680 --> 01:28:58.680
that he was a direct individual,

01:28:58.680 --> 01:29:06.680
and that I had, he had limited discussion with him

01:29:06.680 --> 01:29:12.680
on the involvement of Clyde Kennard in the process.

01:29:12.680 --> 01:29:15.680
I don't know whether that's totally accurate or not.

01:29:15.680 --> 01:29:23.680
He also said that

01:29:23.680 --> 01:29:31.680
Dr. William D. McCain told him that the state of Mississippi higher education

01:29:31.680 --> 01:29:36.680
should be fully desegregated or integrated.

01:29:36.680 --> 01:29:42.680
But the place that it should start should be the University of Mississippi,

01:29:42.680 --> 01:29:48.680
in that we are one vote away from the closing of this school.

01:29:48.680 --> 01:29:55.680
So the delicacy of our standing with the stakeholders

01:29:55.680 --> 01:30:01.680
is such that it ought not start here,

01:30:01.680 --> 01:30:03.680
that we could be closed overnight.

01:30:03.680 --> 01:30:05.680
That's what Lucas told me.

01:30:05.680 --> 01:30:11.680
Why would Southern have been at risk of being closed?

01:30:11.680 --> 01:30:28.680
He explained that our status with the state board was of that nature.

01:30:28.680 --> 01:30:33.680
I don't think I'm led to believe if he's correct,

01:30:33.680 --> 01:30:36.680
there was more than just whether Clyde Kennard came here.

01:30:36.680 --> 01:30:38.680
But in the disturbance here.

01:30:38.680 --> 01:30:39.680
That would be the last.

01:30:39.680 --> 01:30:41.680
That would be the excuse.

01:30:41.680 --> 01:30:48.680
That's what he's constantly told me over the past 30 years.

01:30:48.680 --> 01:30:51.680
That McCain did say he said,

01:30:51.680 --> 01:31:01.680
he said McCain said that Ole Miss should be integrated

01:31:01.680 --> 01:31:06.680
and leave the way, and it would be perfect if Ole Miss

01:31:06.680 --> 01:31:13.680
would be winning the SEC that year.

01:31:13.680 --> 01:31:15.680
So successful school quote,

01:31:15.680 --> 01:31:17.680
these aggregations in Mississippi?

01:31:17.680 --> 01:31:20.680
You know, whether, whether all of that's correct,

01:31:20.680 --> 01:31:25.680
I don't know, but that's what in very serious conversations he's told me.

01:31:25.680 --> 01:31:29.680
Does he raise that or you raise it?

01:31:29.680 --> 01:31:31.680
I've called him and asked him.

01:31:31.680 --> 01:31:32.680
We've met.

01:31:32.680 --> 01:31:33.680
Yeah.

01:31:33.680 --> 01:31:39.680
Because of course he's one of the people that's still living who was actually present for some of that.

01:31:39.680 --> 01:31:40.680
Right.

01:31:40.680 --> 01:31:46.680
Growing up were you aware of his case?

01:31:46.680 --> 01:31:50.680
Oh yes, they talked about it in the beautiful parlour.

01:31:50.680 --> 01:31:55.680
But again, keep it mine, through mine's eye.

01:31:55.680 --> 01:31:58.680
He was a man who got to go to Southern.

01:31:58.680 --> 01:32:01.680
At that time I only knew of one black.

01:32:01.680 --> 01:32:02.680
There was that Southern.

01:32:02.680 --> 01:32:08.680
His name was Mr. Pally and he sold peanuts.

01:32:08.680 --> 01:32:12.680
So he would come out here and stand and sell peanuts.

01:32:12.680 --> 01:32:13.680
Big difference.

01:32:13.680 --> 01:32:15.680
Yeah.

01:32:15.680 --> 01:32:20.680
Did your parents talk about it at all?

01:32:20.680 --> 01:32:22.680
No, not in my presence.

01:32:22.680 --> 01:32:24.680
But the ladies would in the beautiful parlour.

01:32:24.680 --> 01:32:30.680
And keep it mine, Mr. Jean was instrumental always in the inebrile ACP.

01:32:30.680 --> 01:32:40.680
So you always had that from Mr. Jean and she was a beautician also.

01:32:40.680 --> 01:32:43.680
Up on Mopil Street.

01:32:43.680 --> 01:32:46.680
In the 500, 600 block of Mopil Street.

01:32:46.680 --> 01:32:52.680
And they had a shoe shine parlour.

01:32:52.680 --> 01:32:58.680
And her church, which AME African Methodist Episticle,

01:32:58.680 --> 01:33:08.680
has always had a lead in the civil rights.

01:33:08.680 --> 01:33:12.680
I'm glad you brought her up again.

01:33:12.680 --> 01:33:17.680
We interviewed both Ms. Daisy Harris Conner and Mr. Clarence McGee.

01:33:17.680 --> 01:33:20.680
I think you also mentioned as a teacher.

01:33:20.680 --> 01:33:35.680
Can you do it great if you could describe them for having this crossover with the interviews?

01:33:35.680 --> 01:33:39.680
I think Ms. Conner was a willing worker.

01:33:39.680 --> 01:33:48.680
She was hands and feet to the movement.

01:33:48.680 --> 01:33:54.680
Found way of records, found way of history and involvement.

01:33:54.680 --> 01:33:58.680
Gosh.

01:33:58.680 --> 01:34:08.680
She was kind of a...

01:34:08.680 --> 01:34:12.680
Mr. Thun.

01:34:18.680 --> 01:34:20.680
I remember Mr. McGee.

01:34:20.680 --> 01:34:26.680
He was my 10th grade science teacher.

01:34:26.680 --> 01:34:38.680
I never was privileged to conversation with him until 15, 20 years ago with his NAACP.

01:34:38.680 --> 01:34:43.680
And Favonett.

01:34:43.680 --> 01:34:47.680
I think his intentions are honorable.

01:34:47.680 --> 01:34:55.680
Some were dated.

01:34:55.680 --> 01:35:00.680
And what I mean by that is...

01:35:00.680 --> 01:35:06.680
There are some people that would think that the only place you can get a quality education will be all-corn.

01:35:06.680 --> 01:35:18.680
And their love and insight for all-corn supersedes the highest order that Harvard University would offer.

01:35:18.680 --> 01:35:22.680
I'll put it in his fears.

01:35:22.680 --> 01:35:40.680
So I think his limits would prevent inside growths.

01:35:40.680 --> 01:35:49.680
So this is a good moment I think to talk about Southern and how much it's changed in the last 50 years.

01:35:49.680 --> 01:35:55.680
When I was growing up in the Mississippi, there was still in the 70s and early 80s.

01:35:55.680 --> 01:36:04.680
My impression was that there was still a pretty stark divide between the three major white universities and the HBC News.

01:36:04.680 --> 01:36:15.680
And so even at that point, I think where we went to school, there was the impression that Southern was the most welcoming of the three white institutions, perhaps African American students.

01:36:15.680 --> 01:36:23.680
Can you describe Southern today and how it fits in this, how it's changed?

01:36:23.680 --> 01:36:37.680
Well an inside joke is that USM is the Mississippi's fourth HBCU.

01:36:37.680 --> 01:36:42.680
I don't know whether that's kind of not to say.

01:36:42.680 --> 01:37:00.680
I think it's positive from the perspective that we do a tremendous job to a shoe access.

01:37:01.680 --> 01:37:24.680
And we do a tremendous job to provide services to students where they are.

01:37:25.680 --> 01:37:29.680
Is it an open access school?

01:37:29.680 --> 01:37:33.680
In terms of entrance, ACT and all, no.

01:37:33.680 --> 01:37:42.680
It has the same entrance requirements at home and state and all-con valley.

01:37:42.680 --> 01:37:46.680
All the schools have the same.

01:37:46.680 --> 01:37:58.680
The difference might be that one institution might commit that we're going to recruit 60% from out of state and their financial strength allows for that to occur.

01:37:58.680 --> 01:38:08.680
So they may have 60% of their income and students from the state of Texas.

01:38:08.680 --> 01:38:15.680
And those may have not been admitted to the University of Texas at Austin, Texas Christian.

01:38:15.680 --> 01:38:22.680
Southern Methodists are rice, but they may bring 28 ACTs.

01:38:22.680 --> 01:38:36.680
USM's catchment area is roughly 120, 125 miles, primarily first generational.

01:38:36.680 --> 01:38:48.680
I hope this does not sound egotistical, but I know what I needed when I got here in 1970.

01:38:48.680 --> 01:39:01.680
And since my arrival, I've tried to broaden that across the full breadth of this institution.

01:39:01.680 --> 01:39:11.680
From Gondor Dr. Lucas Day-Won, Santa, we need an office of inclusion to talk into athletics about in-service training for guys.

01:39:11.680 --> 01:39:14.680
They work with students at risk.

01:39:14.680 --> 01:39:23.680
From constantly talking about the need for campus wide, services and civility training.

01:39:23.680 --> 01:39:33.680
Because many of the students that will come will be rough on the edge and they'll do things that will jeopardize the educational setting.

01:39:33.680 --> 01:39:46.680
The creating an office of a student's office, busman services to deal with those idiosyncces that kids come to school with that average faculty knows nothing about.

01:39:46.680 --> 01:40:07.680
To be only 24-hour call to manage the almost all foreseeable and all predictable.

01:40:07.680 --> 01:40:36.680
And I think as a result of that, over time through the deficiency or the combination of all, the word is gotten out that you can get from here to there by going to USM.

01:40:36.680 --> 01:40:45.680
If that makes sense.

01:40:45.680 --> 01:40:56.680
Now, I left USM and went to UK, we came to Kerr University and ran a program called Students Services.

01:40:56.680 --> 01:41:12.680
It was for the academic, the high risk that had deficits in three cores, academic, social and financial.

01:41:12.680 --> 01:41:19.680
And we tried to make sure that financially the needs were met.

01:41:19.680 --> 01:41:27.680
There was tutoring to help with deficits and there was counseling to help with our social efforts.

01:41:27.680 --> 01:41:40.680
We ran that program for three years and we went into a catchment area of 30 miles to bring in 100 kids that we leveled the 12th graders to William Kerr plus we worked with them when they were there.

01:41:40.680 --> 01:42:01.680
Then I left never wanted education again and went into alcohol and drug treatment, ran four clinics, New Augusta, Columbia, Purvis, Columbia and here at night.

01:42:01.680 --> 01:42:13.680
And actually came here in 1979 to work until a friend completed his doctorate in two years at the University of Texas at Denton.

01:42:13.680 --> 01:42:15.680
That was how many years ago?

01:42:15.680 --> 01:42:17.680
About 37.

01:42:17.680 --> 01:42:21.680
But it was kind of.

01:42:21.680 --> 01:42:26.680
When you were talking about Southern and Access and you know you can get a good education, you can get reading.

01:42:26.680 --> 01:42:29.680
What's the percentage of African American students my campus?

01:42:29.680 --> 01:42:37.680
Closing around 40% and my rate that there were more African American students at Southern than in other schools.

01:42:37.680 --> 01:42:39.680
Correct.

01:42:39.680 --> 01:42:44.680
So that's got to be a tremendous shift from 50 years ago.

01:42:44.680 --> 01:42:46.680
Certainly.

01:42:46.680 --> 01:42:49.680
But I think we've been accommodating.

01:42:49.680 --> 01:43:01.680
I think I really think on that student affairs side, Dr. Joe Paul would have been here the scope of time.

01:43:01.680 --> 01:43:08.680
I have been here in Dr. Lucas.

01:43:08.680 --> 01:43:20.680
It's been a goal and aim to afford kids access to.

01:43:20.680 --> 01:43:30.680
So do you think, I mean, you know my sense is it's somewhat superficial, but that you know even after James Meredith went to Ole Miss,

01:43:30.680 --> 01:43:39.680
that the people that followed him continued to really struggle, but it was not a particularly that it remained a hostile space.

01:43:39.680 --> 01:43:50.680
But it sounds like you came to Southern five years after the first two students to desegregate it and didn't find that kind of a hostile.

01:43:50.680 --> 01:43:57.680
You think that Southern made a different commitment?

01:43:57.680 --> 01:44:11.680
You know, if you look at the struggles across the country be it with housing, affordability be it with somebody here in this town,

01:44:11.680 --> 01:44:25.680
or some bodies, despite our challenges, cut those sharp edges off.

01:44:25.680 --> 01:44:29.680
I think N.R. Burger was a part of that formula.

01:44:29.680 --> 01:44:43.680
I think Dr. J. Ralph Noonkester, William Carey, I think they collaborated to integrate William Carey to be the first private college in the state to do so.

01:44:43.680 --> 01:44:48.680
N.R. Burger selected those students from Roy and I 1965.

01:44:48.680 --> 01:44:54.680
I think that had been a discussion beforehand with N.R. Burger, Dr. J. Ralph Noonkester.

01:44:54.680 --> 01:45:00.680
I think N.R. Burger, N.R. Burger, Dr. Lucas, and the powers that be.

01:45:00.680 --> 01:45:07.680
I think it got crossed-hired with a lot of people looking at N.R. Burger moving here and there.

01:45:07.680 --> 01:45:12.680
That's why I said his walk I think was so delicate.

01:45:12.680 --> 01:45:23.680
I think another person involved in that, though a lot of people spoke ill, may have chained.

01:45:23.680 --> 01:45:34.680
And others, Moran Pope, a former mayor here leading proponent of the USM.

01:45:34.680 --> 01:45:39.680
I think there were enough people that kept talking.

01:45:39.680 --> 01:45:47.680
Do you think the fire bombing of the Vernon Dahmer Hall and murder of Mr. Vernon Dahmer did that?

01:45:47.680 --> 01:45:51.680
So, there was a wake up call for people.

01:45:51.680 --> 01:46:02.680
I mean, I've heard that you mentioned the president of William Carey that Mr. Vernon Dahmer said that he helped try to raise a little bit of money to rebuild the house.

01:46:02.680 --> 01:46:11.680
To the white community, to the white community, react to that was sort of like it is really too far.

01:46:11.680 --> 01:46:13.680
Is I guess the impression I got into that?

01:46:13.680 --> 01:46:17.680
Does that then create more space for the people who want to do something?

01:46:17.680 --> 01:46:29.680
I think there has been more willingness to work together than not.

01:46:29.680 --> 01:46:37.680
I think in the midst of free and controversy, over time that I'm aware,

01:46:37.680 --> 01:46:54.680
they have been the currents of conversations with folk talking that has worked to us not becoming, has some of the cities have.

01:46:54.680 --> 01:47:02.680
You mentioned when we were talking earlier that you're on the, is it the Civil Rights Museum Commission?

01:47:02.680 --> 01:47:04.680
What's the title of the group?

01:47:04.680 --> 01:47:06.680
Civil Rights Commission.

01:47:06.680 --> 01:47:08.680
Commission. Can you talk about the commission?

01:47:08.680 --> 01:47:32.680
Yeah, it's a Mississippi legislative act that one call for the creation of a civil rights component into the curriculum of the public schools.

01:47:32.680 --> 01:47:47.680
I work from the William Winter Institute for Racial Reconciliation with William Winter, Ms. Susan Glisson.

01:47:47.680 --> 01:47:50.680
The McCombs schools have done a lot of that.

01:47:50.680 --> 01:47:53.680
The schools have done a lot of that.

01:47:53.680 --> 01:48:05.680
So we meet monthly, sometimes quarterly, looking at ways of means to best do that.

01:48:05.680 --> 01:48:19.680
And I also sit on the Mississippi Coalition Against Sexual Assault whereby we look at it employing tactic skills and programming that prevents stalking.

01:48:19.680 --> 01:48:24.680
Violence against women.

01:48:24.680 --> 01:48:26.680
Is that a new commission?

01:48:26.680 --> 01:48:29.680
No, it's us.

01:48:29.680 --> 01:48:32.680
Six to eight years.

01:48:32.680 --> 01:48:53.680
So we've pulled to get all campuses in the state to be an arm to minimize, uh, elax of women, female, as well as others, respect for humanity.

01:48:53.680 --> 01:49:11.680
So all of those things, uh, I think have led to a, and all of my fortunes, I've tried to bring them locally, a guy that I met in 1970.

01:49:11.680 --> 01:49:14.680
Why, okay.

01:49:14.680 --> 01:49:22.680
I said, Eddie, I paid for you to be a member of the, and you've been accepted to leadership in Mississippi.

01:49:22.680 --> 01:49:24.680
Never heard of my life.

01:49:24.680 --> 01:49:35.680
So I went, it's a six month program on developing leadership and making Mississippi better.

01:49:35.680 --> 01:49:41.680
And you look at some aspects of the state.

01:49:41.680 --> 01:49:51.680
It's status where you would think it could get better and you map and design ways from those study committees that you could make that happen.

01:49:51.680 --> 01:49:59.680
Well, once I complete that, came and organized and formed Leadership Hattiesburg, Mississippi.

01:49:59.680 --> 01:50:04.680
A wholesale integrated body of young professionals.

01:50:04.680 --> 01:50:14.680
We're in our 25th year of staffing 20 people up and coming to make Hattiesburg, Mississippi better.

01:50:14.680 --> 01:50:26.680
And as I say before, I'm not in the sand that there are no yields, that there are no situations or impropriety or inequities.

01:50:26.680 --> 01:50:43.680
And maybe I'm blind as a, but I believe that attitude, understanding, uh, hard work, not knowing every time that you'll get what you want.

01:50:43.680 --> 01:50:50.680
That you could impact humanity by way of race.

01:50:50.680 --> 01:51:02.680
I'm not saying even where I've gone, that I've felt welcome, that I've just been an ingratiation that Eddie's here.

01:51:02.680 --> 01:51:13.680
But if I sense that there will be another time when I'll have an opportunity to say hello and to build a bridge.

01:51:13.680 --> 01:51:16.680
Now sometimes that's misunderstood.

01:51:16.680 --> 01:51:22.680
That scene is kissing, hugging inappropriately.

01:51:22.680 --> 01:51:27.680
I say you build a bridge.

01:51:27.680 --> 01:51:33.680
And it may not be strong enough for me to go across it, but maybe tomorrow someone else can.

01:51:33.680 --> 01:51:38.680
Is the Civil Rights Commission involved with the Civil Rights Museum?

01:51:38.680 --> 01:51:41.680
Yes, there are two separate boards.

01:51:41.680 --> 01:51:55.680
We met with them four or five months ago to see the elements of their preparation for the Mississippi History Museum and the Civil Rights Museum.

01:51:55.680 --> 01:52:00.680
So, Mr. Susan Glisson is connected to all.

01:52:00.680 --> 01:52:02.680
She's one of the connectors.

01:52:02.680 --> 01:52:12.680
And many members and former members of both the ALF.

01:52:12.680 --> 01:52:21.680
Yeah, I don't know what the latest is, but can you just tell us a little bit about the plans for the museum?

01:52:21.680 --> 01:52:30.680
I'm not familiar with all of the plans other than what I was privileged when I went to there.

01:52:30.680 --> 01:52:34.680
They had hired the architect for rendering.

01:52:34.680 --> 01:52:50.680
They had hired the programming group to make sure that Mississippi's story was inculcated into the fiber.

01:52:50.680 --> 01:52:59.680
But for me, the challenge would be that you must exit with the dream as opposed to exit with an agony.

01:52:59.680 --> 01:53:01.680
How do you tell the story?

01:53:01.680 --> 01:53:06.680
So, that was my challenge.

01:53:06.680 --> 01:53:16.680
People when they exit, they should not be so marked with the negatives that they don't have a dream for the future.

01:53:16.680 --> 01:53:24.680
Well, certainly. A lot of movement activism in Mississippi is inspiring even if the results are always what people hoped.

01:53:24.680 --> 01:53:31.680
I want to click.

01:53:31.680 --> 01:53:46.680
So, what, I mean, you spoke to that, I think a little bit with your comment just now, but what do you want people to know about the Civil Rights Movement?

01:53:46.680 --> 01:54:09.680
I think the Civil Rights Movement was a breathtaking eye-opening opportunity to see tomorrow from where we stood.

01:54:10.680 --> 01:54:29.680
And to take advantage of those resources that those brought from a yonder here to aid and assist us.

01:54:30.680 --> 01:54:43.680
I think the ingenuity and or the strength was with those that were still here.

01:54:43.680 --> 01:55:07.680
But because they were so linked and wired to their oppressors, other oppressors, strengths that it would have taken longer had there not been a voice of freedom coming from a wealth of places that could speak to that for us.

01:55:08.680 --> 01:55:19.680
So, it gave us a greater opportunity to see life from a distant and to see new possibilities and new beginnings.

01:55:19.680 --> 01:55:31.680
And I think those that were wholesale against it could no longer just see it as those people that were basically here that we are taking care of.

01:55:31.680 --> 01:55:37.680
And how are they disrespecting our efforts?

01:55:37.680 --> 01:55:57.680
But that was a, that it allowed Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia to see that we are behind in the wholesale efforts of equality and services to the least of us.

01:55:57.680 --> 01:56:26.680
And that unless there are some economic gains and heaping doses of educational advancement, we will not have a society of people that are able to pursue dreams that will allow them to reap the freedoms of our people.

01:56:27.680 --> 01:56:33.680
And that would put this great land of forwards.

01:56:33.680 --> 01:56:39.680
That would be a great stopping place, but I did think of another question I wanted to ask you about the movement era.

01:56:39.680 --> 01:56:45.680
And I don't know if you would know about, did you know about the spirit?

01:56:45.680 --> 01:56:47.680
Yes.

01:56:47.680 --> 01:56:51.680
Can you talk about them?

01:56:51.680 --> 01:56:54.680
Well, coming up, I never knew who the spirit was.

01:56:54.680 --> 01:57:09.680
I didn't know that during the times when schools were, or places where businesses were boycotted, that if you break those lines, that the spirit would visit you during the night, things that they can.

01:57:09.680 --> 01:57:16.680
So, what did that mean for people who don't know what the spirit is? What would it mean to be visited in the night?

01:57:16.680 --> 01:57:22.680
Well, goodness, I mean, you never knew who the spirit was, maybe your next to a neighbor, maybe person across the street.

01:57:22.680 --> 01:57:28.680
I remember the spirit by virtue of me wanting to start cutting hair at 11 years of age.

01:57:28.680 --> 01:57:35.680
And I couldn't go to a store and buy hair clippers.

01:57:35.680 --> 01:57:41.680
So, I ordered them at age 11 from National Bellas Hess.

01:57:41.680 --> 01:57:47.680
I don't know if either of us are old enough to know, is a mail order business.

01:57:47.680 --> 01:57:57.680
It was a precursor, maybe, to Best Buy and others, but you could buy hair clippers and pants and luggage and other things.

01:57:57.680 --> 01:58:03.680
And it came to the store on Front Street.

01:58:03.680 --> 01:58:05.680
It didn't come to your house.

01:58:05.680 --> 01:58:07.680
But I couldn't go down there and get them.

01:58:07.680 --> 01:58:17.680
So, I remember calling and they mailed me my walls clippers to the house.

01:58:17.680 --> 01:58:27.680
So, it was a source of economic steering where it called to the attention of those,

01:58:27.680 --> 01:58:36.680
the movers and shakers in our community that people have galvanized, they understand economics to an extent,

01:58:36.680 --> 01:58:48.680
and that if you don't afford them access or at least representation in your stores, that their dollars will not be good enough for you.

01:58:48.680 --> 01:58:56.680
And unfortunately, in this country, wealth is a motivator.

01:58:56.680 --> 01:59:02.680
Frederick Herzberg, but it can be a demotivator.

01:59:02.680 --> 01:59:07.680
That in time, if it demotivates, people will act to that.

01:59:07.680 --> 01:59:11.680
You know, I was against the effort of the kids there at University of Missouri.

01:59:11.680 --> 01:59:16.680
I always had a favorable opinion of University of Missouri.

01:59:16.680 --> 01:59:25.680
Dr. Oval Strickland, profound from Hattiesburg, wrote the school song of Euro and Eureka.

01:59:25.680 --> 01:59:34.680
It was just premier there. Maybe half dozen of our faculty members had gone to journalism there.

01:59:34.680 --> 01:59:39.680
But I don't think any of that would have galvanized until the football team said no.

01:59:39.680 --> 01:59:46.680
And that wasn't a million dollars. That was probably 50 million that weekend had they not played.

01:59:46.680 --> 01:59:49.680
So, the dollar...

01:59:49.680 --> 01:59:52.680
That was going to be a big cost.

01:59:52.680 --> 02:00:01.680
And so, what would the spirit do if somebody from the black community would go into one of the stores that was being boy-todders?

02:00:01.680 --> 02:00:10.680
From what I remember, they may break your windows at your house or your car or may publicize something to you, love you.

02:00:10.680 --> 02:00:18.680
In Hattiesburg, was the spirit also involved in self-defense? Did they do protection as well?

02:00:18.680 --> 02:00:19.680
Well...

02:00:19.680 --> 02:00:20.680
That's separate groups.

02:00:20.680 --> 02:00:25.680
Well, I don't know whether that was the defense. They used to call it the decons of defense or whatever.

02:00:25.680 --> 02:00:35.680
And whenever there would be dignitaries come like Dr. King or Dr. Vivian or Shuttlesworth or some of the other people coming to the area, they would provide security.

02:00:35.680 --> 02:00:43.680
That would double dose that of their own security as well as what your local authorities would give.

02:00:43.680 --> 02:00:47.680
Are there other things you can think of that I haven't asked about that.

02:00:47.680 --> 02:00:50.680
That are important.

02:00:50.680 --> 02:01:01.680
Well, I would think it would reflect of me in terms of my thoughts relative to leadership and relative to civil rights that...

02:01:02.680 --> 02:01:28.680
I think we, in my mind, people that were on the inside of the civil rights movement, maybe were less heralded, but were able to negotiate and accomplish far more than maybe many that had great posture and absorbed the television screens.

02:01:28.680 --> 02:01:30.680
You know, somebody had to do the work.

02:01:30.680 --> 02:01:52.680
And I've always thought it best for me to work from the inside and to work from the strengths that we have, be of bridges, have open lines of communication.

02:01:52.680 --> 02:02:02.680
And from that will come, great outcomes. I would hope that the University of Southern Mississippi, as it looks today, is in part because we did it right.

02:02:02.680 --> 02:02:11.680
You know, it's in part because I've not been a silent observer.

02:02:11.680 --> 02:02:23.680
You know, I've gone to Dr. Lucas, I've gone to Dr. Tim, I've gone to all of the presidents of things that I see that will benefit this institution.

02:02:23.680 --> 02:02:31.680
And in particular, African American students that will come with a wealth of needs.

02:02:31.680 --> 02:02:38.680
Still, most of our communities are separate when it comes to residential or of our religious faith.

02:02:38.680 --> 02:02:50.680
Still, many students bring to the platform deficits. And in particular, African American students.

02:02:50.680 --> 02:03:04.680
And we must be purveyors of good teaching and insightful teachings.

02:03:04.680 --> 02:03:14.680
And to know that if it's preventable, if it's foreseeable, you can prevent it.

02:03:14.680 --> 02:03:35.680
If it's predictable, you can better manage it. So if you're going to have students coming with low ACT scores, transfer from junior college with great needs, that you should have a service of kind to aid in assisting them, that their failures are in part on them and their families.

02:03:35.680 --> 02:03:46.680
But another part of that is on you because you got them here and you didn't do what you took to service them.

02:03:46.680 --> 02:03:48.680
Thank you very much.

02:03:48.680 --> 02:03:51.680
Thank you. I hope in some way my comments have made sense.

02:03:51.680 --> 02:03:58.680
Absolutely. I very appreciate your interview and time with us.

02:03:58.680 --> 02:03:59.680
So thanks.

02:03:59.680 --> 02:04:00.680
Yeah, yeah.

02:04:00.680 --> 02:04:04.680
Well, you just mentioned knowing the ladder sisters from Hattiesburg or Paulmers, right?

02:04:04.680 --> 02:04:05.680
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

02:04:05.680 --> 02:04:06.680
And you tell us about them?

02:04:06.680 --> 02:04:10.680
Well, let's see, I shared dinner with them several months ago.

02:04:10.680 --> 02:04:17.680
We went to the unveiling of the photo of Clark and Art in DC.

02:04:17.680 --> 02:04:26.680
Coming up, they were just household stories of their works at Jackson State in Tougaloo.

02:04:26.680 --> 02:04:32.680
And that Palmer's Cross and was a stronghold for civil rights effort.

02:04:32.680 --> 02:04:41.680
Kelly Settlement, Palmer's Cross and a lot of people saw those communities as communities of need.

02:04:41.680 --> 02:04:45.680
But the strengths were that those people owned their property.

02:04:45.680 --> 02:04:52.680
And they found, I guess, they answered the question that God was making people,

02:04:52.680 --> 02:04:56.680
but they weren't making more land. So they got them a piece of land.

02:04:56.680 --> 02:05:04.680
And the connection of Brown University with Tougaloo, I met Miss Holahan,

02:05:04.680 --> 02:05:10.680
Caucasian lady, the first delta in the country, graduate of Tougaloo.

02:05:10.680 --> 02:05:14.680
So I've just always been a student.

02:05:14.680 --> 02:05:20.680
Is that Joan Trumpauer Mulholland, I don't know what her last name is now?

02:05:20.680 --> 02:05:23.680
I think it's her.

02:05:23.680 --> 02:05:25.680
Well, she's got another one.

02:05:25.680 --> 02:05:27.680
There's a whole of Harlem.

02:05:27.680 --> 02:05:28.680
Harlem.

02:05:28.680 --> 02:05:29.680
Joan Trumpauer Mulholland.

02:05:29.680 --> 02:05:30.680
Joan Trumpauer Mulholland.

02:05:30.680 --> 02:05:31.680
Yeah.

02:05:31.680 --> 02:05:32.680
That's right.

02:05:32.680 --> 02:05:34.680
I know you're talking about her.

02:05:34.680 --> 02:05:37.680
Yeah, because she was out there Tougaloo with them.

02:05:37.680 --> 02:05:38.680
Right.

02:05:38.680 --> 02:05:46.680
But they still have relatives and hadies, but just from reading to them.

02:05:46.680 --> 02:05:49.680
That's one thing that I failed to tell you.

02:05:49.680 --> 02:05:54.680
And I'm sure they missed this at Haddie'sburg High and other schools.

02:05:54.680 --> 02:05:59.680
Those instructors would link you to the precursors.

02:05:59.680 --> 02:06:04.680
And if there was a person living in Detroit doing well from Haddie'sburg,

02:06:04.680 --> 02:06:13.680
Pennsylvania, New York, or California, or they would give you that connection.

02:06:13.680 --> 02:06:22.680
And for me, I would always say, gosh, they get to that location from right here.

02:06:22.680 --> 02:06:26.680
Yeah, it's interesting because I think both of them,

02:06:26.680 --> 02:06:29.680
but I know Dora has been very explicit with me.

02:06:29.680 --> 02:06:33.680
You know, she found it so upsetting that with two colleges here in the community,

02:06:33.680 --> 02:06:36.680
she had to leave for her education.

02:06:36.680 --> 02:06:38.680
It's interesting.

02:06:38.680 --> 02:06:41.680
So from your perspective, come behind you see where they go.

02:06:41.680 --> 02:06:42.680
Yeah.

02:06:42.680 --> 02:06:46.680
And I never expected they wish they had the opportunity to stay like you did.

02:06:46.680 --> 02:06:51.680
Well, I just, and again, for me, I never focused on color.

02:06:51.680 --> 02:06:55.680
I was sensitive of color and race, but I never focused on it.

02:06:55.680 --> 02:07:02.680
I never became a slave to whole limited year,

02:07:02.680 --> 02:07:06.680
I bet you they are not going to like me to have that mindset.

02:07:06.680 --> 02:07:11.680
Or I've got to do this, and I've got to do that because,

02:07:11.680 --> 02:07:20.040
how it is, when I walked on and I saw that all my instructors were Caucasian, I knew

02:07:20.040 --> 02:07:21.040
they would feel this.

02:07:21.040 --> 02:07:24.880
I mean, I never had that.

02:07:24.880 --> 02:07:32.440
I've been conscious that I'm African-American, but I didn't see that as a minus.

02:07:32.440 --> 02:07:33.920
Does that make sense?

02:07:33.920 --> 02:07:39.320
I saw that there may be things that they don't know that I need to share with them, or

02:07:39.320 --> 02:07:44.360
there may be experiences of which they've not been afforded, and I may need to share

02:07:44.360 --> 02:07:45.360
that with them.

02:07:45.360 --> 02:07:54.440
It's kind of like, in closing out, was in a city and a psychologist came out laughing.

02:07:54.440 --> 02:07:57.000
I said, what's going on?

02:07:57.000 --> 02:07:58.400
She's not going to believe it.

02:07:58.400 --> 02:08:00.000
I said, what?

02:08:00.000 --> 02:08:05.440
She says I was doing this psychological assessment on this little girl, and I just had to come

02:08:05.440 --> 02:08:09.240
out and then want to laugh in her face.

02:08:09.240 --> 02:08:10.840
So, what happened?

02:08:10.840 --> 02:08:20.720
She said, I asked her to name three animals, and she said Milton de Masta, Godzilla, and

02:08:20.720 --> 02:08:24.560
the book of men.

02:08:24.560 --> 02:08:29.600
And she says, that's pathetic.

02:08:29.600 --> 02:08:36.320
I say, no.

02:08:36.320 --> 02:08:40.880
I always had to go to bed at night in a dark room.

02:08:40.880 --> 02:08:44.920
Other book of men was going to give me.

02:08:44.920 --> 02:08:50.800
Godzilla was the only movie we had at Star Theatres.

02:08:50.800 --> 02:08:54.680
It stayed there ten years.

02:08:54.680 --> 02:09:00.960
So in that kid's mindset, those were three animals.

02:09:00.960 --> 02:09:02.920
Did that make sense?

02:09:02.920 --> 02:09:07.400
So that kid was okay.

02:09:07.400 --> 02:09:14.520
I was talking about this student who was in trouble and had an accident from a process.

02:09:14.520 --> 02:09:21.800
And actually, probably skilled enough to play on Sunday, if you know what I mean.

02:09:21.800 --> 02:09:29.880
But because of his attitude and what he had said, led to him being an accident, the process.

02:09:29.880 --> 02:09:36.280
But I think my style has always been to share information and to, for insight purposes.

02:09:36.280 --> 02:09:50.600
So if this guy had an opportunity to play for USC or for University of Texas or Oklahoma,

02:09:50.600 --> 02:09:53.680
but his grandmother said no, go to USC.

02:09:53.680 --> 02:09:56.560
I'm that's closer to me.

02:09:56.560 --> 02:09:58.600
And he made that commitment.

02:09:58.600 --> 02:10:08.880
And here she comes up and is diagnosed with the possible terminal illness.

02:10:08.880 --> 02:10:14.480
He didn't go to class because he called her and she said she was feeling real bad.

02:10:14.480 --> 02:10:20.800
But he called the instructor and asked what will be covered.

02:10:20.800 --> 02:10:25.080
But on the report that he didn't go to class.

02:10:25.080 --> 02:10:33.120
He was aggressively, properly though, disciplined.

02:10:33.120 --> 02:10:40.120
But to the point of his pain, he made some very awkward inappropriate statements to the

02:10:40.120 --> 02:10:44.400
power they be.

02:10:44.400 --> 02:10:51.760
I never thought that I was going to change that power opinion.

02:10:51.760 --> 02:11:01.980
But for future references, he needed to understand that this was a grandmother in the absence

02:11:01.980 --> 02:11:12.360
of a mother and a father who said she was sick, who said come to Southern Miss instead of

02:11:12.360 --> 02:11:20.200
those other lofty programs.

02:11:20.200 --> 02:11:27.960
Had the power person asked the right questions, it wouldn't have gone to the extent that it

02:11:27.960 --> 02:11:29.480
did.

02:11:29.480 --> 02:11:39.680
So what I've attempted throughout my walk is to help those have the necessary insights

02:11:39.680 --> 02:11:47.360
to ask the right questions so that they can gain from their view of where the people

02:11:47.360 --> 02:11:55.640
or the person is, be it fighting, be it aggression, be it any of the deficits that our kids

02:11:55.640 --> 02:11:56.640
bring with him.

02:11:56.640 --> 02:12:06.080
They are not excuses for which they should lie on, but they are reasons by which conversation

02:12:06.080 --> 02:12:09.080
hopefully will make them benefit.

02:12:09.080 --> 02:12:10.720
That makes sense.

02:12:10.720 --> 02:12:22.880
So I would hope as a result of those experiences with our students, we have developed a reputation

02:12:22.880 --> 02:12:31.520
that students will come from extreme circumstances knowing that all of this is an historically

02:12:31.520 --> 02:12:33.200
wide institution.

02:12:33.200 --> 02:12:41.680
They will have access to the best and brightest and that the doors will open both ways and

02:12:41.680 --> 02:12:44.840
they will find accommodations.

02:12:44.840 --> 02:12:50.560
That seems like one of those successes in its role, isn't it?

02:12:50.560 --> 02:12:51.560
Yes.

02:12:51.560 --> 02:12:57.000
Thank you so much for your time and for sharing with us today.

02:12:57.000 --> 02:12:58.000
Thank you so much.

02:12:58.000 --> 02:13:00.040
Thank you.

02:13:00.040 --> 02:13:05.000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum

02:13:05.000 --> 02:13:07.560
of African American History and Culture.

